<HEADLINE> Pakistan Prepared to Decrease Regional Tensions in Collaboration with Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DHAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is prepared to work
closely with Bangladesh in lowering tensions in the South Asian
region and promoting peace and stability, said Pakistani High
Commissioner in Dhaka Iqbal Ahmed Khan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's recent letter to
Pakistan Chief Executive General Pervez Musharraf, the diplomat
said Pakistan entirely agrees with the proposals offered by the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
As special envoy of the prime minister, Bangladeshi Foreign
Secretary Shafi Sami visited New Delhi and Islamabad in close
proximity ostensibly in a bid to reduce tensions in the region and
revitalize the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (
SAARC).
</P>
<P>
The South Asian cooperation forum, considered an important
vehicle for expanding cooperation among the member countries and
ensuring peace in the region, remained almost nonfunctional
following military takeover in Pakistan last year.
</P>
<P>
Since then, tensions have also been mounting in the region
centering friction between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
High Commissioner Iqbal said it is extremely important that
the root cause of conflict between India and Pakistan that whipped
up tensions in the region should be addressed with all earnestness.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, the root cause is Kashmir. Once it is resolved,
the countries in the region would be able to harness tremendous
potential that exists in South Asia," Iqbal pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He referred to General Musharraf's offer of no-war pact with
India and mutual reduction of troops, which he made at the United
Nations General Assembly on Wednesday. Musharraf also offered
dialogue with India anytime at any place to defuse the stresses
and strains.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina is scheduled to have a meeting
with General Musharraf early Friday on the sidelines of the U.N.
Millennium Summit. Regional peace and cooperation among the SAARC
nations are likely to feature their talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South-East Asian TB Training to be Held in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The fourth South-East Asian
Tuberculosis (TB) Training is to be held here from September 11 to
enhance the capability of managers involved in the eradication of
TB in the South-East Asian region, according to the joint convenor
of the training.
</P>
<P>
The 11-day training to be held under the joint aegis of the
Nepali National TB Center and the World Health Organization is
expected to add to the effort to control TB, which has assumed
alarming proportions in the region, Miss Jamuna Shrestha, the
joint convenor, told the press Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The training will cover the theoretical issues of TB control,
the use of labs, training supervision and supervision procedures,
drugs management and evaluation, Shrestha said.
</P>
<P>
Some 38 TB control managers from Nepal, India, Bangladesh,
Bhutan, Thailand, Myanmar, Indonesia and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea will participate in the training, she said.
</P>
<P>
Observers from Nepal, Belgium, Germany and Switzerland will
also attend the training, she added.
</P>
<P>
TB is a major public health problem in the South Asian
countries. Statistics shows that the region accounts for over 30
percent of the global TB cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
