<HEADLINE> Canada Announces Entry Into Force Additional Nuclear Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy and Natural Resources Minister Ralph Goodale announced
the entry into force of the country's additional nuclear protocol
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement released here, the Canadian ministers said
their country is meeting its multilateral obligations for the
peaceful use of nuclear energy with the International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA).
</P>
<P>
"The entry into force of Canada's Additional Protocol with the
IAEA will be one of the first by a country with a significant
nuclear program," said Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
"The Canadian Nuclear Safety Commission will be responsible for
implementing the measures Canada has agreed to under the Protocol,
" according to Goodale.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian officials believe that "conclusion of the
Additional Protocol will provide the IAEA with an enhanced ability
to detect undeclared nuclear materials and activities in states."
</P>
<P>
Canada signed the Additional Protocol to its existing
Safeguards Agreement for the protection of nuclear material with
the IAEA on September 24, 1998. 
</P>
