<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Close in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore and his Republican rival George W.
Bush were virtually tied in two news polls published here Thursday,
but Gore has gained an advantage on top issues such as economy,
education and health care.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll conducted by CNN, USA Today and Gallup,
Gore had 47 percent to 44 percent for Bush among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
Another poll by ABC-Washington Post showed that the two
presidential candidates were tied at 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
But another poll of 1,001 by Reuters found Gore led Bush by 46
to 40 percent. The poll was taken Monday through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The polls showed that Gore is gaining momentum in his campaign
after the Democratic national convention. Bush led Gore in polls
taken before the two conventions.
</P>
<P>
The ABC-Washington Post poll showed that Gore has opened up a
50-38 advantage on education, and has a slight edge on managing
the economy and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
He also enjoys a double-digit lead on health care and
environment while Bush has an edge on tax and national defense.
</P>
<P>
While Bush held about a 20-point lead among men, Gore has
opened up an 18-point lead among women in the ABC-Washington Post
poll.
</P>
<P>
The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of 777 likely voters was taken
Monday through Wednesday and has an error margin of plus or minus
4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The ABC-Washington Post poll of 810 likely voters has an error
margin of 3.5 percentage points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
