<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Dissatisfied With Revised U.S. Exports Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Friday expressed its dissatisfaction over a revised exports plan
of the United States, describing it as little more than window-
dressing.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation bloc said it expected to mount a new round of
challenge at the World Trade Organization (WTO) if the proposed
changes were enacted in the U.S. exports plan.
</P>
<P>
The proposed changes were described as "little more than window-
dressing" by one EU official on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We have said clearly that the legislation as it is currently
worded does not address the principal problem that we have with
the Foreign Sales Corporation regime and that it constitutes an
export subsidy and is export contingent," said Anthony Gooch, EU
trade spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress on Thursday agreed to quickly revise the
export program which the WTO found to be an illegal subsidy.
</P>
<P>
But the proposed changes to the program do not satisfy the EU
that had challenged the U.S. Foreign Sales Corporation scheme at
the WTO already.
</P>
<P>
"The system that is being proposed by (the U.S.) congress at
the moment continues to be contingent on exporting. If that
legislation is put into place by October 1, then no doubt we will
take this up with the WTO again speedily to ask whether they agree
with our view that the system is export contingent," Gooch added.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been given by the WTO until October 1 to
work out a replacement program to its Foreign Sales Corporation
scheme to bring it into line with world trade rules.
</P>
<P>
Under WTO rules, if the EU feels that the United States has not
complied with the WTO ruling, it can return to Geneva after
October 1 and ask the WTO dispute panel to rule on the legality of
the revised U.S. program.
</P>
<P>
Should the panel rules against the revised U.S. program, the EU
could seek compensation from the United States or ask WTO
permission to impose sanctions on U.S. goods which could amount to
as much as billions of dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
