<HEADLINE> UK Truck Drivers Protest High Fuel Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Lorry drivers in Britain Friday
caused chaos on a key motorway in a protest echoing that of their
French counterparts to demonstrate against high fuel taxes.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 heavy goods vehicles and tractors took part in a
"go slow" protest on the highway at Gateshead on Tyneside Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A convoy of lorry drivers headed for the Texaco refinery in
Pembroke with the aim of staging a further blockade.
</P>
<P>
Farmers and lorry drivers, angry against high fuel prices, said
the protest was the first of many which would continue over the
weekend and spread across the country.
</P>
<P>
The protest, which coincided with the evening rush hour, lasted
for 90 minutes and thousands of motorists were caught up in
tailbacks.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 40-50 trucks were set to begin blockade of a
Texaco refinery at Pembroke in west Wales Friday night.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to make the government aware of the problems we
face and the fuel companies as well," said protest organizer
Phillip Rees.
</P>
<P>
In France, the five-day fuel blockades were thought to have
left 80 percent of petrol stations dry, with airports beginning to
cancel internal flights because of fuel shortages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, protesting UK farmers and hauliers were still
picketing Shell's Stanlow oil refinery near Ellesmere Port in
Cheshire.
</P>
<P>
A Shell spokesman at Stanlow said the protest would begin to
have an effect on petrol stations throughout the north of England
later Friday.
</P>
<P>
It began as a blockade Thursday but was broken up after police
threatened to arrest them. However, more than 500 members of the
Less Tax on Fuel group have pledged to join the protest from
Friday and over the weekend in shifts.
</P>
<P>
British Transport Minister Lord Macdonald said British
protesters did not have the right to interrupt vital supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
