<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Reaffirms Confederal Solution for Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said Friday that a solution that does not consider the
sovereign existence and equality of "the Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus " as the basis, can not be lasting.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the stance in a written statement before Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash leaves for New York on September 9 to
attend the fourth round of the proximity talks on Cyprus, Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, a Mediterranean island, has been divided into Greek
Cypriots-dominated south and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north
since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the northern third of
the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots proclaimed "the Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus" in 1983, which is only recognized by Turkey. Turkey and
Greece support their side in the island state on ethnic line.
</P>
<P>
U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify the state on a bi-
communal, bi-zonal federation formula, but Denktash, who walked out
of peace talks in 1997, required a confederation of two equal
states on the island.
</P>
<P>
Brokered by the U.N., the sides have held three rounds of
proximity talks since the second half of last year to prepare
grounds for substantial peace talks. But no tangible progress has
been reported.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that "Mr. Denktash proposed a realist arrangement
which foresees cooperation on the basis of a confederal structure
between the two states on the island. We share and support the
proposal of Mr. Denktash."
</P>
<P>
He said that only when the two sides are considered equals, "the
direct and comprehensive negotiations will start. This is the
common understanding of the President Rauf Denktash and us."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Cautions OPEC Members Against Oversupply of Crude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Oil Minister Bijan Namdar
Zanganeh here on Friday told members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) not to make any big increase
in crude output when they meet in Vienna, Austria, next week.
</P>
<P>
OPEC member countries should take into consideration the decline
in world economic growth in order to avoid any imbalance of oil
supply in the market, the minister was quoted by the Islamic
Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that world economic growth forecast is 4.5
percent for the year 2000, while this figure is only 3.9 percent
next year.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh and his OPEC counterparts are to start their regular
meeting in Vienna on Sunday to decide whether to make any further
increase in output to bring down the oil prices.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members, excluding Iraq, have increased oil output quota
twice since March to control rising oil prices. But the prices have
remained high, surpassing 30 U.S. dollars a barrel recently.
</P>
<P>
On the continuous price hike since last month, Zanganeh said it
was not caused by a lack of supply. But he referred to
psychological factors, speculation in the oil market and U.S.
presidential elections as important factors in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He said oil producing countries within OPEC have acted enough
and responsibly in the past few months to stabilize the oil market.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members have actually added 2.5 million barrels per day to
their total production in the past six months, thus effectively
preventing any lack of supply, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
He added that in the past two months, there has been a hike in
crude supply in the market by some 1.5 to 2 million barrels per
day.
</P>
<P>
About Saudi Arabia's reported unilateral increase in supply by
500,000 barrels a day as of July 1, Zanganeh said this has not been
confirmed by his Saudi counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia as a founding member of OPEC is not expected to act
against the organization's collective decisions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh also voiced his concern about world oil producers'
dwindling excess capacity of crude production, which now stands at
less than 2 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Non-OPEC oil producing countries are now doing their best to
produce 49 million barrels per day and the OPEC production stands
at 28.5 million barrels per day, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited dropping of oil income, lacking of investment and U.S.
sanctions on Libya, Iran and Iraq as the main factors blocking the
creation of excess capacity.
</P>
<P>
Iran, as the second largest OPEC producer after Saudi Arabia,
currently pumps some 3.8 million barrels of crude per day, of which
nearly 2.45 million barrels are exported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
