<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Intensifies Strike against Transnational Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has stepped up
fight against transnational crimes with some 70 police officers
having received special training within and outside the country, a
senior police officer said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Ever since the October 1998 U.S. embassy bombing, we have
stepped up efforts to fight transnational crimes," Tanzanian
Director of Criminal Investigation Adadi Rajabu said at a ceremony
in which Tanzanian police accepted drug and explosive search dogs
from their British counterpart
</P>
<P>
Rajabu cautioned that efforts made by the government towards
that end are not enough and that the whole society should join the
fight against terrorism, drug trafficking and arms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
He said the on-going civil war in neighboring Burundi and the
Democratic Republic of the Congo posed threat to the peace and
stability in Tanzania, as armed robbery increased in border areas
with mass influx of refugees and illegal weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
