<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Minister Warns Against Prolonging Oil Refinery Blockade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of Transport
Jean-Claude Gayssot warned the protesting truckers and farmers
Friday evening against prolonging their blockade of oil refineries
and roads.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with France 3 television channel, Gayssot said
that the police force would intervene if the blockade continues
because the country cannot endure an indefinite blockade which has
been going on since Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is very evident that the situation of blockade cannot last,
" he said when asked whether the government is considering
resorting to force to lift the blockade.
</P>
<P>
"We call on everybody to take up his responsibility. The
country cannot be blocked," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
While two national unions of truckers have agreed to lift the
blockade, one last union, the National Union of Syndicated
Organizations of Road Haulers, said it will continue the blockade
until the government meets its demand for further oil tax cut.
</P>
<P>
About 95 percent of the oil stations of the Total-Fina-Elf oil
company and 80 percent of those of the U.S. company Esso have run
out of oil except those on the highways and in the Paris region.
</P>
<P>
The whole French economy is beginning to feel the pinch from
the blockade, as department stores are running out of goods and
airports are canceling flights.
</P>
<P>
The traffic on many highways are being disrupted by protesters
who are staging "snail operation" to block roads.
</P>
<P>
The oil unrest, triggered by sharp rises in oil prices over the
past few months, is also spreading to other European countries,
including Britain, Belgium, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has urged France to stop the blockade which
it says is threatening the economic activities of the whole
continent.
</P>
<P>
In its negotiations with protesters, the French government has
agreed to cut oil tax by 35 centimes (five U.S. cents) a liter
this year and 25 centimes (3.5 U.S. cents) next year.
</P>
<P>
The government has ruled out further concessions because of the
strong opposition to oil tax cutting from the Greens, who make up
part of the left-wing coalition of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
