<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Concerned at Impact of High Oil Prices on Poor Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a statement issued through his spokesman, Annan said the oil
price increase has relieved the financial pressures in major oil
exporting countries, but the potential of a serious impact on
inflation and interest rates in major importing countries remain.
</P>
<P>
In the past, he said, sharp increases in oil prices have
triggered recessions that hurt all countries including the oil
exporters.
</P>
<P>
Expressing particular concern at the adverse effects on oil
importing developing countries, the U.N. chief said high oil bills
could easily jeopardize the first signs of recovery in these
countries.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries are less able to substitute oil by other
energy sources, and their smaller technological and financial
capacity to introduce energy efficient processes and the
increasing burden would result in balance of payments problems and
a reduction in other imports and spending, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The poorest segments of the developing countries will be
hardest hit with an attendant rise in prices of other essential
goods such as fuel, food and transport," he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that major oil producers, which have demonstrated
their willingness to look at oil prices and related supply/demand
issues in a long-term context, would be sensitive to the impact of
their decisions on the world economy, especially on the poorest
countries.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices soared to a 10-year high of 32.85 U.S. dollars a
barrel on Monday. Experts attribute the trend to expectations that
increased production of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) is not enough to compensate for shortages of U.S.
heating oil expected this winter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
