<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Missile Hit Kursk Nuclear Sub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Friday vehemently
denied a German newspaper report that the submarine Kursk, which
sank last month and killed all 118 crew aboard, had been hit by a
guided cruise missile fired by a Russian warship.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Berliner Zeitung report that sub had been sunk by a
Granit missile fired by the Pyotr Veliky cruiser was untrue, said
Igor Dygalo, a Russian Navy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Kursk went down to the bottom of the Barents Sea on August
12 during naval exercises.
</P>
<P>
Dygalo said that missiles and torpedoes used in naval exercises
do not carry warheads, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia's domestic intelligence agency, the Federal
Security Service (FSB), also dismissed the report as "completely
groundless."
</P>
<P>
The German paper said a supposed FSB commission headed by FSB
chief Nikolai Patrushev had come to such a conclusion and reported
it to President Vladimir Putin on August 31.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, who heads a
government commission probing the disaster, also rejected the
German report.
</P>
<P>
"No firing was taking place at the time the Kursk catastrophe
occurred," Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
He said authorities are now considering three possible causes --
a collision with another object, a World War Two era mine, or an
emergency in the first (torpedo) compartment of the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
"All these versions are equally possible," Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
In Severomorsk, the home port of the Northern Fleet, commander
of the Pyotr Veliky cruiser, Vladimir Kasatonov, said he was
outraged by the Berliner Zeitung article.
</P>
<P>
The Pyotr Veliky did carry out "planned" missile launches
during the exercises, Kasatonov said. "In an effort to ensure
security and rule out non-standard situations during training
exercises, areas for every vessel's whereabouts are clearly
designated and sectors and times for missile and torpedo firing
are defined."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Kursk "could not have been in the area of a
missile launched from the cruiser even in theory," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Pyotr Veliky "was participating in the operation to rescue
the Kursk crew up until the last moment," the captain said. "The
sailors did not sleep for days, but none of them took the rest
because everybody knew that we were rescuing our own," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is immoral to blame the cruiser's crew for the deaths of
our friends," Kasatonov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
