<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Not Excluding Euro Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank said
Friday evening that it does not exclude the possibility of
intervening in the market to support the euro, whose exchange rate
has fallen to a record low against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting of finance ministers, representatives of the
European Central Bank (ECB) and the European Commission held in
Versailles southwest of Paris, ECB Vice President Christian Noyer
and French Minister of Finance Laurent Fabius said that "
intervention is an element which remains ready at any moment."
</P>
<P>
Fabius is the current president of the Eurogroup which groups
the finance ministers of 11 euro zone countries and is in charge
of coordinating financial policy with the ECB.
</P>
<P>
The Eurogroup and ECB said in a communique after the meeting
that they are following the situation of euro very closely and are
concerned about the present exchange rate of the single currency
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the euro zone countries are
experiencing "solid growth" and achieving "progress in the fiscal
field."
</P>
<P>
It also said that further structural reforms are needed for the
euro zone countries "in order to increase the potential of growth.
"
</P>
<P>
The euro has fallen 30 percent to 0.87 U.S. dollar, the lowest
since its launching in January 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
