<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Stresses Palestinian Refugees' Right to Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
Friday reaffirmed that Palestinian refugees should go back to their
country, warning that "there will not be a peace without their
return."
</P>
<P>
Lahoud made the remarks when meeting a visiting British
parliament delegation, which is on tour to the region, staring with
Lebanon, to study and assess the situation of the Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
"We will not see the real, just and comprehensive peace unless
the Golan Height is liberated and those Palestinian refugees are
allowed to go back," Lahoud stressed.
</P>
<P>
Roughly 3.5 million Palestinians have been displaced since
Israel was founded in 1948 and they are scattered in Lebanon, Syria
and Jordan. Their return is a key issue in the Palestinian-Israeli
final status talks.
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated that his country does not agree to
discriminate against refugees. "What's the difference between the
refugees after 1948 and 1967?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has hinted that the refugees after the 1967 Mideast war
could return while those in the 1948 exodus will not be granted the
right. About half the refugees in Lebanon came after the first
Middle East war in 1948.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have made it very clear that Lebanon will not host
Palestinian refugees for ever. We will not compromise under
international pressures, nor will we accept them faced up with
substantial lure," the leader said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has strongly favored the leave of the registered 360,000
Palestinian refugees, the key factor behind the 1975-1990 sectarian
war, fearing their stay can tip the sectarian balance again.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, reports revealed that some organizations wanted
to offer Lebanon 20 billion U.S. dollars in return for Lebanon's
nod to nationalize and host the Palestinian refugees for ever. The
president hastened to deny the "rumor" and affirmed the non-
acceptance stance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
