<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Army Names New West Bank Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel Defense Forces (IDF)
General Staff Friday appointed Brigadier General Benny Ganz as the
new commander of Israeli forces in Judea and Samaria, or the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ganz will replace his predecessor Shlomo Oren, who resigned
earlier for a deadly operation mishap, in the next few weeks, an
order signed by IDF Chief of General Staff Shaul Mofaz stated.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of Oren, who took over the command just last
March, was accepted by Mofaz on Thursday when the chief of general
staff presented the investigation findings of the botched raid.
Oren became the highest-ranking officer ever who quit without being
asked to step down.
</P>
<P>
Three soldiers of the elite Duvdevan unit, or special troops in
the West Bank, were killed during the operation two weeks ago, when
their comrades mistakenly identified them as targets and killed
them.
</P>
<P>
One disaster after another, the real hunted man Mahmud Abu-
Hanud, a Hamas extremist, managed to flee from the scene after
being wounded and surrendered himself later to the Palestinian
forces.
</P>
<P>
Before IDF's withdrawal from south Lebanon last May, Ganz was
the head of the IDF-Lebanese Liaison Unit. The career experience in
Lebanon may help Ganz to accommodate himself to the new post, which
was regarded one of the most important position in the IDF,
especially facing the possible conflicts with the Palestinians in
the West Bank in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Liberation Organization's Central Council will
meet Saturday to decide whether to declare an independent state on
September 13 without an Israeli-Palestinian agreement.
</P>
<P>
Some Israelis had warned that such a unilateral action will lead
to large-scale conflicts between the two sides in the occupied West
Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
