<HEADLINE> Egyptian Pilot Bars Israeli Security Officials From Searching Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- An EgyptAir pilot said on Friday
that he had barred armed Israeli security men from searching his
plane at the Palestinian Gaza airport and flew back to Cairo empty
after the Israelis stopped passengers boarding his plane.
</P>
<P>
Captain Ali Murad said upon return to Cairo airport that he had
prevented the Israelis from searching his plane because the
aircraft "is considered Egyptian territory with Egyptian
sovereignty," Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An EgyptAir official at Cairo airport said that Egypt, Israel
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) have an agreement for
Egyptian planes using Gaza airport to be searched by one unarmed
Israeli security official accompanied by an unarmed Palestinian
security official and airline security men, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Murad, who is head of Egypt's Pilots' Union, said that he was
surprised to see his plane surrounded by a number of Israeli armed
security men right after the passengers got off.
</P>
<P>
But "I barred the security men from entering the plane to search
it in accordance with the rules and laws of civil aviation," he was
quoted as saying by the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security services control air traffic in and out of Gaza
under agreements signed with the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian ambassador in Israel, Mohammed Bassiouni, sent a
representative to the airport to intervene, but negotiations failed
to resolve the matter and the plane left for Egypt without its 91
passengers after four hours of delay.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian national carrier later sent another plane to Gaza
to fly the passengers to Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
