<HEADLINE> UNICEF Reiterates Support for Angola's Anti-Illiteracy Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) reiterated here on Friday for the Angolan government
's efforts to provide all the school-age children with quality
education.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a letter to the Angolan government while the world
was marking the International Adult Literacy Day, the UNICEF
delegation in Luanda hailed the success achieved by the Angolan
government in the nationwide campaign for fighting illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2.5 million people have been trained by the programs
sponsored by Angola's Ministry of Education and Culture in the
basic process of communication since 1975 when the country gained
independence, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
It said that "alphabetization corresponds to a fundamental
right of the human being, contributes for his liberation from
alienation and servitude, and constitutes a basic condition for
the democratic way of life."
</P>
<P>
According to a document issued by Angola's News Department, the
illiteracy rate among the Angolan population is estimated at 60
percent, mainly due to the 26 years of rampant civil conflicts
that destructed a lot of schools and displaced 3.7 million
residents, many of them being women and children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
