<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Illiteracy is Only Way to Development: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Fighting illiteracy is the
only way to development, said Rwandan Minister of State for Social
Affairs Odetta Nyiramirimo on Friday at the celebrations to mark
the International Illiteracy Day in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
"Illiteracy is the source of poverty, disease, violence and
sectarianism," he was quoted by Rwanda News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that over 51.8 percent of the Rwandan
population cannot read and write, regretting that the highest
number of illiterates in the country are females, making up 54
percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
"What is painful is that the number of female illiterates who
are 15 years and above increases annually due to poverty and
lagging behind in development," he said, recalling that after the
1994 genocide, 30 percent of the Rwandan families are female-
headed compared with 21 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations Economic Social and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO), "by 2005, over 188 million people from
developing countries will be illiterate, out of which 115 million
will be females, equivalent to 61 percent."
</P>
<P>
The International Illiteracy Day, which falls on September 8
every year, was first cerebrated in 1967 after education ministers
from UNESCO countries met in Iran in 1965. The day is aimed at
reiterating the role of literacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
