<HEADLINE> Toronto International Film Festival Opens With Canada's Stardom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The 10-day Toronto
international film festival opened Thursday night with the
projection of Canada's film Stardom, which closed the Cannes Film
Festival earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
The 25 Toronto International Film Festival "is getting its
biggest influx of stars in years," according to organizers, who
expect more than 500 actors and directors to attend the festival
being held abreast with Cannes, Venice and Berlin.
</P>
<P>
As the celebrities were arriving for last night's gala opening,
stars like Frank Langella and Dan Aykroyd, who are in the opening
night film Stardom, emerged from the fleet of 13 multicolored
Volkswagen Beetles in replacement of the limousines.
</P>
<P>
Stars can be found anywhere with the guest list showing the
likes of Richard Gere, Al Pacino, Robert De Niro, Robert Duvall,
Kenneth Branagh, Robin Wright-Penn, Gwyneth Paltrow, Elizabeth
Hurley, Minnie Driver, Jeff Bridges, Nicolas Cage, Cuba Gooding Jr.
, Kate Hudson, Alec Baldwin, Ben Kingsley, Matthew Broderick,
Willem Dafoe, Ed Harris and Sally Field, organizers disclosed.
</P>
<P>
"It may be the most outstanding list of people I've seen at
this festival. When you have Pacino, De Niro, Duvall, Branagh, you
're dealing with the top of the tops. And these are just the
actors," said festival director Piers Handling.
</P>
<P>
A total of 329 films will be shown during the festival, which
runs between September 7 and 16, with 243 of them being features
and the rest being shorts.
</P>
<P>
Up to 700 buyers and sales agents are also expected at this
year's festival, including 32 new companies from 27 countries.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 6,000 films have been shown at the Toronto International
Film Festival since it was inaugurated in 1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
