<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland to Decide United Nations Accession in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Swiss President Adolf Ogi said
that the Swiss people will decide whether their country should
join the United Nations in a referendum in 2002.
</P>
<P>
"Switzerland shares the United Nations values: peace, stability,
democracy and human rights," Ogi said at the U.N. Millennium
Summit in New York on Thursday. "This is why Switzerland intends
to enhance its relations with the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
What is more, he went on, Switzerland hosts an important
headquarters of the U.N. system in Geneva, but the country itself
is not a full U.N. member.
</P>
<P>
Speaking as the first Swiss president at the U.N. General
assembly, Ogi promised that the Swiss government would put the U.N.
membership issue to the people to determine in two years.
</P>
<P>
According to recent polls, the majority of the Swiss support
the idea to join the U.N.
</P>
<P>
At a recent meeting with a group of journalists in his home
town of Kandersteg, Ogi also talked about Switzerland's relations
with the European Union (EU) and NATO.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no timetable for his country's accession
to the EU although Switzerland has signed bilateral agreements
with it. While Switzerland has taken part in NATO's partnership
program, Ogi said, Switzerland has no intention to join NATO at
present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Has Right to Decide Balkan Policy, Says Hitiris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Greece decided itself what must be its policy in the Balkan
region, said acting Greek government spokesman Tilemachos Hitiris
at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou met with Milosevic in Belgrade Thursday to discuss
the upcoming elections in Yugoslavia, but the U.S. State
Department said that any meeting between a European figure of
Papandreou's stature and persons indicted for war crimes was
unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
Hitiris said that there was nothing Greece could do about it if
the U.S. were not pleased.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister made a wish and a suggestion on the Yugoslav
elections for the benefit of the country itself, he said, adding
that Greece with its presence contributed to stability and peace
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Greece was in favor of the
restoration of a climate of peace, cooperation and economic
development in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Papandreou said Friday that Greece had briefed both
the U.S. and the European Union (EU) over his intention to visit
Belgrade, but Greece did not request authorization as this would
be inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou believed that his contacts with the Yugoslav
leadership were especially useful and his positions were
understood.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister is the only top envoy from an EU country to
visit Belgrade since NATO ended its bombings against Yugoslavia
last June.
</P>
<P>
In Greece, Communist Party of Greece (KKE) Secretary General
Aleka Papariga Friday strongly criticized the Greek government
over its Yugoslav policy, saying that the government was now
trying to influence the result of Yugoslavia's elections, which
are due to take place on September 24.
</P>
<P>
Describing Greece as "the long arm of the U.S. in the Balkans,
Papariga said that Greece had played the role of a partner in
Washington's effort to take over the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
She also voiced strong opposition to the NATO exercise which is
to start in western Macedonia this weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
