<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Hikes Policy Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines decided Friday to raise its policy rates by 100 basis
points effective next Monday, 11 September 2000.
</P>
<P>
The increase brings the overnight borrowing and lending rates
to 11.0 percent and 13.25 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the three-tiered system for overnight
placements of banks will continue to be implemented as follows: an
overnight borrowing rate of 11.0 percent will be offered for
placements of up to 5 billion pesos (11 million U.S. dollars); 9.5
percent for the next 5 billion pesos, and 8.0 percent for
placements in excess of 10 billion pesos (222 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The policy rate adjustments are aimed at addressing emerging
inflationary pressures that could arise from the pass-through
effects of the weakening of the peso-dollar exchange rate," said
the central bank in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The policy rate adjustments are also aimed at addressing the
narrowing differential between domestic and foreign interest rates,
and the consequent shift in investors preference to U.S. dollar-
denominated investments," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate increased to 4.6 percent in August,
the highest level registered in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the peso fell to a record closing low at 45.595
pesos against the U.S. dollar on September 5. The local currency
has fallen almost 12 percent since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said it will continue to monitor development,
and "policy rates will be reviewed and adjusted as may be
warranted by prevailing conditions."
</P>
<P>
However, analysts have expressed concerns the move to raise
interest rates may reverse the economy's recovery, as it could
hamper growth momentum in the banking and property sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
