Russian President Vladimir Putin, British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and U.S. President Bill Clinton attended the summit. (U.N.-
Security Council-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday expressed
regret about a confrontation between officials from the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and U.S. security personnel that
led to the cancellation of the DPRK's participation in the
Millennium Summit, which kicked off Wednesday at the U.N.
headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
Clinton voiced his regret in his meeting with South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung at his hotel in downtown New York, where
the two presidents were meeting on the sidelines of the three-day
summit to discuss the U.N. role in the new century. (Clinton-DPRK-
Regret)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on Friday criticized
Tokyo for arresting a Japanese naval officer on suspicion of
spying for Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Japanese authorities arrested Shigehiro
Hagisakia, a 38-year-old lieutenant commander in the Maritime Self-
defense Forces, on suspicion that he had passed military secrets
to a Russian embassy official for money, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened just days after Russian President
Vladimir Putin's trip to Tokyo. (Russia-Japan-Officer)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- France missed a 24-hour deadline to reply to a
European Union (EU) call to end road blockades that are blamed for
breaching the EU's law of free movement of people and goods.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Todd, spokesman for the European Commission that
serves as the executive body of the 15-nation bloc, said that the
commission has so far received no reply from France to its call to
end the blockades.
</P>
<P>
He said the next step the commission has to take is to send a
formal request to the French authorities who have five working
days to reply how they are coping with the road blockades. (EU-
France-Blockades)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Meimad Movement within the ruling One
Israel bloc has warned it will pull out of the government if bus
and state-run airline El Al service is introduced on Shabbat.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Yehuda Gilad, chairman of the movement secretariat, told
Israel Radio on Friday that such action will border on violations
of the coalition agreement between One Israel and Meimad regarding
the relationship between religion and the state.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who is in New York attending the U.N.
Millennium Summit, has said that buses and El Al will run on
Shabbat. Earlier, Transportation Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak said
that El Al should be allowed to fly on Shabbat to facilitate its
privatization. (Israel-Shabbat-Secular) 
</P>
