<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Household Spending Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Filipino families increased
their spending for household furnishings, transportation and
communication and other miscellaneous items by 5.7 percent during
the first half of the year, an institute report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The National Science and Development Board (NSDB) on the
economy said the increased family spending contributed to the
better-than-expected growth of the economy for the same period.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) increased by 3.9 percent in
the first semester of 2000 which was 1.7 percentage higher
compared to the 2.2 percent gain for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The NSDB said in its research report that spending for personal
consumption, which grew 3.2 percent, accounted for 75 percent of
the GDP growth during the first semester of 2000.
</P>
<P>
This hike in personal consumption expenditure was brought about
by a corresponding increase in spending for household furnishings
such as electrical and recreational video appliances, the NSDB
said.
</P>
<P>
Spending on transportation and communication also posted an
accelerated growth of 7.5 percent due to "the phenomenal rise in
cellular and landline phone subscriptions," it added.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures on miscellaneous goods and services went up by 4.4
percent during the first half of the year, with medical and health
services, personal care and effects as among the biggest
contributors in this sector.
</P>
<P>
"All other spending priorities of families such as on household
operations; fuel, light and water; clothing and footwear also
ticked positive growths," the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
