<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore-NZ Free Trade Pact to Boost Cooperation: PM Goh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore-New Zealand
Free Trade pact, nearing completion, will give a boost to greater
arrangements between regions such as ASEAN and Australia and New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The local Channel News Asia (CNA) Friday quoted Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong, who is in New York attending the UN
Millennium Summit, as speaking this to the media with his New
Zealand counterpart Helen Clark.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders enthused about the Agreement between New Zealand
and Singapore on Closer Economic Partnership (ANZSCEP) which will
be signed soon.
</P>
<P>
Goh said its success would be the start to a similar agreement
between ASEAN and Closer Economic Relations (CER) countries,
Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
That is due by the year 2010 but he stressed such agreements
are to facilitate rather than replace the freeing up of
multilateral trading.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement scraps tariffs and export subsidies and
liberalizes access to each other's services sectors.
</P>
<P>
Goh said the agreement will mean Singapore can tap into New
Zealand's skilled professionals, something he has often said the
country needs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the two leaders is one of many bilateral talks
held on the sidelines of the UN Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
Goh also met with Botswana President Festus Mogae and the
International Labor Organization's chief Juan Somavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
