<HEADLINE> South Korean Energy Imports Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has spent 20.9
billion U.S. dollars on energy imports during the first seven
months of this year, up 91.4 percent from the same period of 1999,
said the Ministry of Commerce, Industry and Energy on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Imports of crude oil hit a record high of 14.1 billion U.S.
dollars, surging 105.4 percent and accounting for 67 percent of
the total energy imports, while imports of liquefied natural gas (
LNG) totaled 2.06 billion U.S. dollars, up 104.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, domestic energy consumption in January-July
increased 7.9 percent over the same period of last year, and that
of petroleum and nuclear power rose by 4.9 percent and 9.3 percent
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
