<HEADLINE> Canadian Former PM Trudeau Reported "Seriously Ill" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Former Canadian Prime Minister
Pierre Trudeau is "seriously ill" at his home in Montreal with his
former wife Margaret and two sons gathering at his bedside, media
here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Trudeau's sons Justin and Sacha said in a brief statement
Thursday that their 80-year-old father "is not well" and is "
resting comfortably with his family and receiving medical
attention."
</P>
<P>
They requested the family's privacy be respected.
</P>
<P>
Trudeau's former wife Margaret was seen arriving by car late in
the afternoon after the news of Trudeau's illness first broke at
about 13:15 local time (1815 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Trudeau, who turns 81 next month, is reported to be suffering
from Parkinson's disease. He "never recovered from the pneumonia
he had last winter," according to one of his friends, Senator
Serge Joyal.
</P>
<P>
"He is 80 years old and he doesn't have the same capacity as
someone 20 or 30 years old. But it has no impact on his mind. He
is as sharp as usual," said the senator.
</P>
<P>
Trudeau was prime minister between 1968 and 1979 and from 1980
to 1984. During his term of office, Canada came through the first
challenge to its national unity in the referendum on the future of
the French- speaking province of Quebec in 1980. The country
normalized relations with China on October 13, 1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
