<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Troops to Clear Mines for Inter-Korean Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Some 2,800 South Korean troops will
begin mine clearing and road work late this month for the planned
inter-Korean railway and highway projects, said the Defense
Ministry on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under a comprehensive plan for the projects, the ministry said
it will also mobilize 324 pieces of heavy equipment, including 22
water sprinklers and 48 excavators.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the railroad and highway projects will
require 32.5 billion won (some 29 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ministry said all areas south of the Demilitarized Zone (
DMZ) and within the zone itself subject to mine removal are 560,
000 square meters, which consist of 240,000 square meters for the
severed rail link and 320,000 square meters for the new highway.
</P>
<P>
At the historic inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang on June 13-15,
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and leader of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Kim Jong Il agreed to relink the
railroad between Seoul and Shinuiju, a DPRK city bordering China,
which was severed before the Korean War in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to complete the restoration of a 20-kilometer
rail section across the DMZ within one year. South Korea plans to
restore a 12-kilometer rail section between Munsan and Changdan.
</P>
<P>
The mine-clearing work is expected to take three months for the
4.1-kilometer railroad project and five months for the highway
project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
