<HEADLINE> Singapore's Disabled Athletes Leave for Paralympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is sending two
athletes to Sydney to take part in the Paralympics, the
international sports meet for the disabled, which will take place
right after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The athletes are Azman bin Yusof, a track and field runner who
has cerebral palsy, and Zaimoonisah binte M Mohd Yussoff, a
visually disabled cyclist, with her sighted partner.
</P>
<P>
Both have competed regionally and internationally and done well.
</P>
<P>
Azman, who will be participating in the 100 and 200 meter races,
recently won three gold medals at the ASEAN invitational
championships in Kuala Lumpur in May.
</P>
<P>
Zaimoonisah, who is visually disabled and can only see up to
five to ten meters ahead of her, used to be a runner but this time,
she will be riding a tandem bicycle with her sighted partner.
</P>
<P>
Zaimoonisah, who will compete in three events, was expected to
bring back at least a medal in the one kilometer time trial.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has been competing in the Paralympics since 1988.
</P>
