<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Ruling Religious Faction Warns Against Secular Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Meimad Movement
within the ruling One Israel bloc has warned it will pull out of
the government if bus and state-run airline El Al service is
introduced on Shabbat.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Yehuda Gilad, chairman of the movement secretariat, told
Israel Radio on Friday that such action will border on violations
of the coalition agreement between One Israel and Meimad regarding
the relationship between religion and the state.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who is in New York attending the U.N.
Millennium Summit, has said that buses and El Al will run on
Shabbat. Earlier, Transportation Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak said
that El Al should be allowed to fly on Shabbat to facilitate its
privatization.
</P>
<P>
According to Judaic laws, Jews should not do such secular things
as flying, driving or selling things on Shabbat, the Jewish holy
day which lasts from Friday's sunset to Saturday's sunset.
</P>
<P>
The strict rule on secular activities has aroused
dissatisfaction among secular Jews who are less observant of the
Judaic laws. This constitutes part of the conflict between them and
the observant Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
Meimad leader and Minister of Israeli Society and World Jewish
Communities Rabbi Michael Melchior, who has accompanied Barak to
New York, told Israel Radio Friday that Meimad is prepared to give
up on religious legislation aimed at forcing an observant way of
life on the Israeli citizens.
</P>
<P>
But the movement, the only religious faction left in the
coalition following the resignation of the National Religious Party
(NRP) and the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party in July, is not willing to
cede the Jewish character of the state and the Jewish identity of
its citizens.
</P>
<P>
Moni Mordechai, spokesman of Israeli Society and World Jewish
Communities, told Xinhua that "Shabbat is the mutual basis for the
Jewish people. It is not a practical but rather a cultural thing."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Meimad is not against providing bus
services to the secular people but that should be done within a
covenant.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement between One Israel and Meimad acknowledges
that Israel is a democratic and Jewish state whose Jewish
characters will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Barak would certainly meet strong
opposition if he tries by coercion to implement the transportation
service on Shabbat.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that with the early elections looming,
Barak's bid to open bus and airline service on Shabbat is aimed at
attracting secular voters who have deserted him over the fact that
the prime minister who had given in to a series of demands put
forward by the religious Shas party and that he had neglected
social and economic issues due to his concentrated efforts on the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak's remarks are also seen as a prelude for his new coalition
efforts upon returning from the U.N. Millenium Summit to rebuild
his shaky government left in tatters following the resignation of
former coalition partners in protest of his peace policies.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, stalled since the July Camp
David summit, failed to achieve a breakthrough at the ongoing U.N.
Millennium Summit which was widely seen as a good opportunity for
the two sides to hold further talks and bridge their differences.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton launched what he called the last
peace effort at the summit, conducting shuttle talks between the
Israelis and Palestinians. He decided to give up his efforts after
the U.S. proposals on the issue of Jerusalem was again rejected by
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Forms Committee to Beef Up E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Law Ministry is
forming a committee to coordinate efforts to enhance the country's
e-commerce legal infrastructure and legal competency.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister of State for Law and Home Affairs Ho Peng
Kee announced the plan at a Singapore IT Dispute Resolution
Advisory Committee seminar Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new committee will draw its members from the Infocomm
Development Authority (IDA), the Singapore Academy of Law, the
Singapore Law Society and the National University of Singapore law
faculty.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Subordinate Courts will soon take measures to
facilitate the mediation of e-disputes within cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
"For e-commerce to thrive and develop in an orderly fashion, it
will be necessary for both to establish a comprehensive legal and
regulatory framework, and develop the requisite legal expertise to
support the demands that the e-commerce industry will generate,"
Ho said.
</P>
<P>
The IT industry and IT users must realize the need for them to
increase their awareness of the legal implications of e-commerce,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The legal profession must likewise develop greater legal
expertise in e-commerce related matters, and in this way, meet the
challenge of supporting Singapore's bid to be an international
center for e-commerce, he said.
</P>
<P>
To deal with e-disputes expected to accompany the advent of e-
commerce, IDA is working with various government agencies to put
in place a complete legal framework for the e-commerce environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
