<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sulu Hostages' Release Fails to Push Through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The scheduled release of the
six remaining foreign hostages held by Abu Sayyaf in Sulu
province in the southern Philippines on Friday failed to push
through after negotiators cited various reasons for the delay.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference in the southern Zamboanga city,
Philippine chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado cited the
death of Abu Sayyaf leader Mujib Susukan's brother and unusual
movements by the extremists as the cause for the delay.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado said Friday evening in the televised press
conference that the burial of Susukan's brother was a factor in
the delay because some Abu Sayyaf leaders had to attend the burial
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"The other cause of the delay is the reported trouble created
by the Abu Sayyaf members in Maimbong town where Commander Robot (
Abu Sayyaf leader Galib Andang) had to rush to pacify the
community," Aventajado said.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf members in motorcycles went around Maimbong town in
Sulu province and harassed residents there, explained Aventajado.
</P>
<P>
The chief negotiator didn't specify any new date for the
release of the six remaining foreign hostages, including three
French, two Finns and one German. Some reports said they might be
released on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sources privy to the negotiations claimed the
shortage of ransom money was one of the main reasons for the delay
of the release.
</P>
<P>
They said Libyan officials who arrived in Philippines Tuesday
brought only 4 million U.S. dollars as the Abu Sayyaf has
allegedly demanded a one-million-dollar ransom for each of the six
foreign hostages.
</P>
<P>
The botched release was supposed to be follow-up to the freedom
of six other foreign hostages who were released last month.
</P>
<P>
A South African couple, three French and a German national left
the Philippines on August 28 and returned to their respective
countries after their four-month ordeal in the hands of the Abu
Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
The hostage saga began in April when the Abu Sayyaf abducted 21
mostly foreign hostages from the diving resort of Sipadan island
in Malaysia. Sixteen of the original 21 hostages have been
released so far after 11 million dollars ransom was reportedly
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the remaining five Sipadan hostages, the Abu Sayyaf
is also holding two French journalists and 12 Filipino evangelists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
