<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Donors Pledge New Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-five donor members of
the Asian Development Bank (ADB) have agreed on a 5.6-billion-U.S.-
dollar total replenishment of the Asian Development Fund (ADF),
the bank said Friday in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said the pledge was announced after the fifth and final
donors' meeting in Okinawa, Japan, this Thursday.
</P>
<P>
ADF VIII, as the current replenishment is called, will cover
the four-year period 2001 to 2004. The replenishment compares
favorably with a total of 5.1 billion dollars in loan approvals
expected under ADF VII, covering the period 1997 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
ADF loans are provided on concessional terms to ADB's poorer
developing members with limited debt repayment capacity.
</P>
<P>
They support poverty reduction through pro-poor sustainable
economic growth, the provision of social development such as
education and health care, and the strengthening of good
governance.
</P>
<P>
Under the new replenishment, donors agreed to contribute a
total of 2.91 billion dollars. The balance of the replenishment is
expected to be met from repayments of earlier loans.
</P>
<P>
Japan remains the largest ADF contributor with 1.061 billion
dollars. The United States will contribute 412 million dollars,
while the European donors will make a total contribution of 860
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1973, the ADF has played a significant role in
promoting sustainable economic development in low-income members,
particularly benefiting disadvantaged and vulnerable groups.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1999, ADF loans amounted to 22.7 billion dollars,
or 28 percent of cumulative ADB lending. In 1999 alone, 33 ADF
loans were approved amounting to 1.1 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
