<HEADLINE> Drought Costs Tajikistan 57 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Severe drought this year will
cost Tajikistan an estimated 57 million U.S. dollars and many
residents of the Central Asian republic need assistance in food
and seeds, an international humanitarian agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Roger Bracke, who led an assessment and coordination team of
the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies, said they visited 14 Tajik areas hardest hit by the
drought and found the situation far worse than expected.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference in the capital city of Dushanbe, Bracke
said his team will appeal for help for 250,000 recipients in seven
districts of Khatlon and Leninabad regions as they are in severe
shortage of foodstuffs and seeds, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik Red Crescent Society wants flour and vegetable oil
sent to residents of Northern Ganchi and Zafarabad districts and
to the southern towns of Kulyab, Farkhor, Dangara, Vose and
Shaartuz before the onset of winter, which will close access to
many of the remote areas, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is Tajikistan's largest economic sector involving a
population of about 6 million. Some 68 percent of the total
population live in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan is mostly mountainous, with only 6 percent of its
land cultivated. Lowland is in the extreme north and in the lower
reaches of the tributaries of the Amu Darya River in the southeast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
