<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak to Invite Likud into His Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak will invite the major opposition Likud party to join his
government once he returns from New York, Israeli Communications
Minister Binyamin Ben Eliezer revealed Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is a move that may cast clouds over the Israeli-Palestinian
peace track as the right-wing Likud is opposed to further
compromise to the Palestinians, local analysts believed.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel Radio reports, Ben Eliezer, who is now
acting prime minister as Barak is abroad, confirmed that the Likud
will be the first party invited by Barak to begin coalition talks
on building up a national unity government.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who is now in New York to attend the United Nations
Millennium Summit, lost his parliamentary majority ahead of the
Camp David summit with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in July and
is eager to restore his control in the parliament, which is
scheduled to re-convene at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that to work with Likud indicates that Barak, who
had set the peace as his top priority after he assumed office in
July last year, may finally feed up with the zigzagging of the
peace process and want to change his agenda.
</P>
<P>
Such an alliance with Likud will surely put the domestic
economic and social issues ahead of the peace talks, the analysts
claimed.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian talks had been in deadlock since the
Camp David talks, under the guidance of U.S. President Bill
Clinton, failed to reach any agreement due to significant gaps
between the two sides over the fate of Jerusalem and the return of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's latest efforts -- separate meeting with Barak and
Arafat on the sidelines of the Millennium Summit -- also failed to
bridge gaps between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Although Barak said at a new conference Thursday night that he
believed the door for peace talks is still open, Israeli delegates
accompanying him to New York admitted privately that the dominant
mood in Barak's camp is pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
Danny Yatom, Barak's confidant and senior adviser, Friday told
Israel Radio that he is not sure if Israel and the Palestinians
could reach an agreement in the near future, although efforts to
revive the negotiations should still be made.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear whether Likud Chairman Ariel Sharon, who
repeatedly denied in the past that his party would join Barak's
government, will change his mind. Sharon said Thursday that he will
commit himself to toppling the government, which he claimed had
conceded too much to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
However, Ben Eliezer said Friday that he is confident that the
Likud will accepted Barak's invitation and join the cabinet once
the party understands the prime minister's stands on all core
issues regarding Israel's security and civil reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
