<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Services Industry Expands in 2nd Quarter 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's services
industry expanded by 3.8 percent in the second quarter 2000 over
the same period last year, said the Singapore Department of
Statistics (SDS) Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increase was indicated by the Quarterly Business Receipts
Index (QBRI) for Services Industries, an indicator for monitoring
the current performance of Singapore's services sector.
</P>
<P>
SDS attributed the expansion to double-digit growth in the
business receipts of insurance services, post and
telecommunications, business, professional and air transport
services.
</P>
<P>
The insurance industry expanded by 47 percent in the second
quarter this year, boosted by a strong demand for single premium
life insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, financial services which was affected by the
sluggish stock market dropped by 11 percent in business receipts.
</P>
<P>
With the strong growth in air traffic, air transport services
increased by 14 percent in revenue.
</P>
<P>
Land transport services also improved by 8.5 percent, while
water transport services dropped by 5.3 percent compared with the
second quarter 1999.
</P>
<P>
Post and telecommunications performed well for the second
consecutive quarter, rising 17 percent in business earnings.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, IT services grew 5.6 percent in business receipts in
the second quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
Professional services rose by 15 percent in the second quarter
this year, largely due to higher turnover of legal activities,
business management and consultancy services, consultant
engineering services, and accounting and auditing services.
</P>
<P>
Business increased by 6 percent on the back of better
performance in advertising, labor recruitment services, exhibition
fair and convention services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
