<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Eases Censorship in Run-up to General Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has eased some censorship regulations in the run-up to
the October 10 general elections, a government spokesman said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Director of Information Ariya Rubasinghe said the president had
eased the censorship effective from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, he said there are still restrictions against reporting
on internal squabbles within the military and military operations
against Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels are fighting a 17-year war against majority
Sinhalese dominated government in a bid to carve out a separate
state for minority Tamils in the country's north and east.
</P>
<P>
The blanket censorship was imposed on May 3 this year when
government troops were struggling to resist a major offensive
launched by LTTE rebels in the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The move of easing censorship came five days after the New York-
based Committee to Protect Journalists urged President Kumaratunga
to lift the censorship ahead of the elections. The local Free
Media Movement had also urged the government to lift the
censorship.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga also lifted a ban on public meetings in
view of the elections. The campaign began earlier this week after
nominations closed for the 11th parliamentary general elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
