<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Increase Oil Quota for Local Explorers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
concluded plans to increase oil quota for indigenous petroleum
explorers and producers as the price of oil in the international
market continues to rise, the Post Express newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new concessions were part of a comprehensive package to
wake up local industrialists to engage more in the upstream sector
of the oil industry, Nigerian Vice President Atiku Abubakar was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the members of the Nigerian Association of
Indigenous Petroleum Explorers and Producers (NAIPEC) in the
capital Abuja on Thursday, Abubakar said the government plans to
increase their quota from 15,000 barrels per day to 25,000 barrels
per day.
</P>
<P>
The government would also review the 1991 policy which allows
local explorers to participate in the oil industry, and remove the
obstacles that stand against local investment and turnover in the
oil industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the indigenous oil production policy has to be
reconsidered especially in the area of the structure of allocating
marginal fields in blocks earlier handed over by major oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
However, the vice president noted that the proposed new
legislation, which is expected to come on stream by 2003, would
define operatorship and contain provisions for adjustable tax rate,
royalty rate and investment tax allowance.
</P>
<P>
On his side, NAIPEC National President Alhaji Salah Mohammed
Jambo said the removal of the restriction on oil production quota
would free resources for more aggressive exploration and
production program.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to stop the Nigeria National Petroleum
Corporation from intervening in the formulation of policy for
local oil producers.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is the biggest oil-producing country in Africa with a
daily output of more than 2 million barrels, but most of them are
produced by foreign oil companies operating in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
