<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Reply Yet From France to EU on Road Blockades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- France missed a 24-hour
deadline to reply to a European Union (EU) call to end road
blockades that are blamed for breaching the EU's law of free
movement of people and goods.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Todd, spokesman for the European Commission that
serves as the executive body of the 15-nation bloc, said that the
commission has so far received no reply from France to its call to
end the blockades.
</P>
<P>
He said the next step the commission has to take is to send a
formal request to the French authorities who have five working
days to reply how they are coping with the road blockades.
</P>
<P>
The blockades have severely disrupted France's public road
traffic as truck drivers blocked fuel depots and farming truckers
and taxis jammed streets to protest the ever-rising prices of fuel.
</P>
<P>
Todd warned that the commission would have to take France to
court should it fail again to reply within the new deadline.
</P>
<P>
But the proceedings at the European Court of Justice usually
take 18 to 24 months before giving a verdict on the case, long
after the road blockades have ended.
</P>
<P>
The French government has already cut down taxes levied on fuel.
Tight production policy adopted by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) has contributed to the recent oil price
hike on international markets.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices now seemed determined to fluctuate within a
band of 30 U.S. dollars a barrel and it entered that band in
February this year following an uninterrupted rise since December
1998 when the crude oil price bottomed out at 10 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Fadhil Chalabi, executive director of the Center for Global
Energy Studies, warned earlier this week that "if OPEC does not
increase its production, prices will go very high until the peak
of the winter. Prices may even exceed 40 dollars a barrel."
</P>
<P>
OPEC, scheduled to meet over this weekend in Vienna, is
expected to approve an additional production of 500,000 barrels a
day. However, analysts say that amount may not suffice to meet the
demands worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
