<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Publishes First Health Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
Friday published its first public health data, a reference for
those EU citizens who are curious and cautious about health.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Key Data on Health," the statistical guide tells
people how many EU citizens are satisfied with their health; what
the differences are between EU member states concerning the
diseases of cancer, tuberculosis and hepatitis; which member state
has the highest ratio of doctors to the total population, and how
many organ transplants are carried out in the EU.
</P>
<P>
The data of the reference guide comes from Eurostat, the World
Health Organization, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization,
the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, the
International Agency for Cancer and the AIDS Surveillance Center.
</P>
<P>
Covering all the 15 EU member states as well as Iceland, Norway
and Switzerland, the first-ever statistical guide reports that
satisfaction with personal health posts the highest in Finland (78
percent), Austria (71 percent), the Netherlands (70 percent),
France (60 percent) and Belgium (56 percent), while
dissatisfaction is the lowest in Portugal (73 percent), Greece (65
percent) and Italy (50 percent).
</P>
<P>
The guide shows epidemic diseases and cancers are reported as
the number one and two killer diseases in the EU, accounting for
40 percent and 30 percent of deaths respectively. They are
followed by respiratory diseases, accidents and suicides.
</P>
<P>
Greece boasts of the highest ratio of doctors to the total
population with 933 doctors per million inhabitants, while the
Netherlands has the lowest ratio of 356 doctors per million
inhabitants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
