<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Plans to Cut Back 350,000 Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev said Friday that the Russia Armed Forces would be reduced
by 350,000 troops in 2001-2003, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Decisions to that effect have been made and proposals on how
to proceed are being drafted for the president," Interfax quoted
Sergeyev as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the ground force is to be cut by 180,000
troops, the navy by more than 50,000 and the air force by nearly
40,000. Strategic missile units, logistics and auxiliary services
will also be slashed significantly, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Among other military services, the Interior Ministry's interior
units will be cut by 20,000 troops, the railroad units by 10,000
and the Federal Border Guards Service by 5,000.
</P>
<P>
The strength of other military agencies, in particular the
Federal Government Communication Service and the Federal Security
Service, will be cut by nearly 25,000 men, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
