<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atmospheric Monitoring Automation In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to realize
automation in the field of atmospheric monitoring in the coming
years after completion of the world's most advanced monitoring
system.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a total investment of over 30 million yuan (
about 3.6 million U.S. dollars), will be launched in northwest
China's Qinghai Province, aiming to monitor disastrous weather.
</P>
<P>
Experts say atmospheric detection is the foundation of
meteorological study. And the atmospheric environment on the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau has great influence on the climate of China
and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In the light of frequent disastrous weather on Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, the completion of the project will increase the accuracy
and capability of weather monitoring, said Wang Jiangshan,
director of the Qinghai Provincial Meteorological Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring system, based on over 30 climatic and
meteorological stations in the province and advanced equipment
imported from Finland, will be used to detect barometric pressure,
temperature, humidity, wind direction and power, precipitation,
radiation and other meteorological factors.
</P>
<P>
Li Huang, vice director of China Meteorological Bureau said the
project is the start of China's automation in ground detection. In
addition, over 800 automatic meteorological stations will be set
up across China in the future years.
</P>
<P>
Li added that China will expand cooperation with other
countries in the field of meteorological research and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
