<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't Forms Team to Investigate Atambua Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A team consisting of
representatives of the Indonesian military, police and the
Attorney General's Office has been formed to investigate the
recent killing of three United Nations aid workers in the town of
Atambua in East Nusa Tenggara province, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Indonesian Defense Force (TNI), Adm Widodo AS,
said here Friday that the team has begun to question some people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesian Police chief, Gen. Rusdihardjo, said they
have investigated at least 15 East Timorese refugees over their
alleged involvement in the attack on the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
The 15 suspects were arrested Thursday for their suspected in
Wednesday attack against civilian U.N. staff.
</P>
<P>
Three UNHCR staff were killed on Wednesday when hundreds of pro-
Jakarta East Timor militiamen attacked the U.N. envoy's office in
Atambua bordering with East Timor which got independence one year
ago from the rule of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Rusdihardjo said the investigation touched only their alleged
involvement in the attack and murder.
</P>
<P>
"We have so far not found any political reason (behind the
attack)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Widodo and Rusdihardjo both expressed regret over the incident,
which they said has destroyed Indonesia's image in the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Widodo further said that the military has deployed one
battalion from Solo, Central Java, on Friday to reinforce the
battalion deployed to Atambua on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid during his meeting with U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan in New York on Thursday promised that
Indonesia would immediately send two battalions to Atambua to
contain the situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesian government on Friday reminded the U.N.
Transitional Authority in East Timor and the East Timorese
Resistance Committee to work together with Indonesia to resolve
the problems in the refugee camps which are located along the
border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
