<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, ILO Sign Agreement to Eliminate Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government and
the International Labor Organization (ILO) have signed an
agreement on the elimination of worst forms of child labor in
Nepal, an ILO official told Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed here Thursday, the Nepali
government will rectify by the end of this year the Convention 182
adopted by the International Labor Conference in Geneva in 1999,
concerning the prohibition and immediate action for the
elimination of the worst forms of child labor, said Yadav Amatya,
national program manager with ILO.
</P>
<P>
To this effect, the Nepali government is developing a 10-year
Master Plan of Action, which will aim at eliminating the worst
forms of child labor by 2005 and all forms of child labor by 2010,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Convention 182 stipulates that the worst forms of child
labor comprises sale and trafficking of children as compulsory
laborers, sex workers or sex slaves, employment of children in
hazardous work, use of children for illicit activities and
compulsory recruitment of children for use in armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The master plan also include a pilot project which will provide
skill training programs to child labor-prone families in 7 of the
72 districts of Nepal and help create self-employment
opportunities for adults, said Amatya.
</P>
<P>
Poverty, especially high unemployment of adults, is the main
cause for the wide use of child laborers in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Statistics shows that of about seven million children of 5-14
years old in Nepal, about three million are found to be regularly
working and 1.7 million children are found to be economically
active. As Nepal is an agrarian country where about 85 percent of
the people live on agriculture, over 90 percent of the child
laborers are living in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
