<HEADLINE> Track-Laying Starts on New Southwest Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Track-laying began today on a
new railway linking Neijiang with Kunming, cities in southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the 879-kilometer-long railway is a state key
project. It will be part of the country's north-south railway
trunk. Its operation will alleviate the transportation tension in
southwest China and speed up tourism and natural resources
development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The line starts from Neijiang City of Sichuan Province and runs
through several cities in Sichuan, Guizhou and Yunnan provinces
before ending at Kunming, provincial capital of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
The track is scheduled to be joined at Zhaotong in Yunnan on
October 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The railway is expected to cost an estimated 11.6 billion yuan
(1.4 billion U.S. dollars), with funds from the Ministry of
Railways and the governments of Sichuan, Guizhou and Yunnan
provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
