<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Find New Immune Molecule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists recently
claimed to discover a new type of immune molecule, which could be
used for fighting against cancer and deadly infections.
</P>
<P>
Cao Xuetao, a professor with the No. 2 Medical Sciences
University of the People's Liberation Army (PLA), led the research
group, which discovered the molecule, a chemotactic factor
consisting of 77 amino acids.
</P>
<P>
In the well-known Immunology Journal which is published in the
United States, the research group named the molecule MIP-gamma 2,
whose gene is embodied in kidney tissue and the small intestine.
The new find made by the Chinese scientists is said to be a
breakthrough in the research of immunology.
</P>
<P>
Using gene-engineering technology, Cao and his colleagues
separated the new-style molecule from the dendritic cell's gene
pool.
</P>
<P>
The discovery bears academic significance to the understanding
of vital phenomena in the human body, and pathogenesis of many
diseases, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the immune molecule also has important clinical
value, which can provide new remedies or high-tech biologic
medicine to immunity-related diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Control of Precursor Chemicals in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Precursor chemicals refer to
chemical material and reagents that could be used to illicitly
manufacture or synthesize narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Although many precursor chemicals are not narcotics themselves,
they are usually necessary elements for the production or
synthesis of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
According to a United Nations pact in 1988, a total of 22 kinds
of precursor chemicals, including ephedrine, has been placed under
tight control. As a signatory state to the pact, China is no
exception.
</P>
<P>
China has one of the toughest controls on ephedrine, a
substance that could be used to manufacture "ice", one of the most-
abused central stimulant in the world.
</P>
<P>
In March 1998, the State Council issued a circular, clarifying
the responsibilities shouldered by different government
departments in the manufacturing, trading, storage, transportation,
as well as the import and export of ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, the ministry of public security promulgated a
regulation to tighten the issue of transportation permits for
ephedrine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
