<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
highlights of cultural news stories Xinhua released from September
1 to 7:
</P>
<P>
-- Int'l Cultural Festival Held at Mount Lushan
</P>
<P>
The 2000 Lushan International Cultural and Tourism Festival
opened on September 1 at Mount Lushan, a world culture heritage
site, attracting 1,000 visitors from both China and overseas.
</P>
<P>
The organizers have planned colorful activities for festival
participants including evening concerts, a world table tennis
champions competition, sightseeing and a seminar on the research
of Taoism.
</P>
<P>
-- 2000 Tibet Yalong Cultural Festival Opens
</P>
<P>
The 2000 China Tibet Yalong Cultural Festival opened on
September 1 in the Yalong scenic spot at Zedang Township, Shannan
Prefecture of the Tibet Autonomous Region, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
The four-day festival, which has been held successively for
three years, is aimed to help with the research and development of
Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
-- Rock Paintings Make Debut for Visitors
</P>
<P>
A gallery of rock paintings at Mount Helan in northwest China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region was opened to visitors on September
3.
</P>
<P>
An international symposium on rock paintings was also held,
attracting more than 130 Chinese and foreign scholars.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the tens of thousands of rock paintings carved
by nomads in northern China some 2,000 years ago at Mount Helan
are of great historic, artistic and scientific value, and Ningxia
will become a center of world rock painting research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Guizhou to Host Ethnic Garment Festival
</P>
<P>
Guizhou Province in southwest China will host a major cultural
festival displaying the traditional garments of ethnic minorities
on October 3-4.
</P>
<P>
The festival will feature a dozen ethnic groups including, Miao,
Yao, Shui and Zhuang. Many of the ethnic groups, especially the
Miao and Dong ethnic groups, have rare and special dress styles,
ornaments, handicrafts and arts.
</P>
<P>
-- China's First Family Culture, Art Festival Opens
</P>
<P>
China's first Family Culture and Art Festival opened on
September 3 in Dongguan City of Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Selected families across the country performed programs
including songs, dancing and gymnastics at the opening ceremony of
the festival.
</P>
<P>
During the 23-day festival, calligraphy, drawing, photography
and invention exhibitions, family sports meetings, gardening shows
will be held.
</P>
<P>
-- Museum of Silk Road Schemed in Xinjiang
</P>
<P>
China will turn the existing museum in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region into a technologically advanced one, showing
treasures found on the ancient Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
The country will pour 110 million yuan (about 13.3 million U.S.
dollars into the renovation project, which is scheduled to be
completed in 2005.
</P>
<P>
-- China to Hold International Expo on Stamps, Coins
</P>
<P>
The south China city of Guangzhou will hold a stamp and coin
exhibition on the theme of Beijing's bid for hosting the 2008
Olympic Games from October 31 through November 3.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that China hosts an international
professional exhibition on stamps and coins after those in Beijing
and Shanghai in 1995 and 1997, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
