<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Economic Growth Hits Six Percent in FY 1999/2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's real economic growth
rate in the fiscal year 1999/2000 ending on July 14, 2000, stood
at 6 percent, the highest in six years, while inflation
decelerated to 3.3 percent, according to Nepal Rastra Bank, Nepal'
s central bank.
</P>
<P>
The impressive economic growth, compared to 4.0 percent in the
previous fiscal year, was achieved thanks to improvement in
agricultural sector followed by marked growth in manufacturing,
electricity and trade sectors, said a press communique by the
Nepal Rastra Bank, available Friday.
</P>
<P>
Due to a fall in the prices of food and beverages, the annual
average national consumer price index recorded a rise of 3.3
percent compared to a rise of 11.3 percent in the previous year,
said the communique.
</P>
<P>
Despite a higher growth rate of exports than imports, trade
deficit increased by 6.7 percent, amounting to 55.34 billion
rupees (790 million U.S. dollars), mainly because of relatively
larger volume of imports compared to exports, it said.
</P>
<P>
Exports and imports registered respective growths of 44.7
percent and 22.2 percent, standing at 51.6 billion rupees (737
million dollars) and 107 billion rupees (1.53 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nepal's economy had been in continuous recession since 1992/
1993 fiscal year when it grew by 7.2 percent. In the last six
fiscal years, the economy grew by an average of 3.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
