<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Finance, Central Bank Deputies Meeting Ends in Brunei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bandar Seri Begawan, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Finance and
Central Bank deputies of the 21 APEC members concluded their two-
day meeting here Friday with a proposal for a policy dialogue for
strengthening corporate governance in the APEC region.
</P>
<P>
The proposal will be referred to APEC Finance Ministers for
consideration at their 7th meeting here on September 9-10, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The deputies hold that the policy dialogue will provide a
valuable forum for open and constructive discussion of corporate
governance issues relevant to APEC economies.
</P>
<P>
They said in a press release that if Finance Ministers agree,
the policy dialogue will take place in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
The deputies discussed a New Zealand-led collaborative
initiative intended to promote freer and more stable capital flows
in the APEC region. The proposal assesses the benefits and risks
of opening economies to capital flows, and highlights policies
which could maximize benefits while minimizing risks.
</P>
<P>
The deputies discussed APEC leaders' directives on financial
market issues, banking standards and measures to enhance the
effectiveness of APEC Finance Ministers through stronger links
among the various APEC fora, and an APEC Forum on Shared
Prosperity and Harmony.
</P>
<P>
They discussed several other new initiatives including social
safety nets, managing regulatory change in life insurance and
pensions, company accounting and financial reporting, paperless
trading, strategic objectives for the APEC Finance Ministers
process, and an enhanced role in the fight against abuse of the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
The deputies reviewed global and regional macroeconomics and
financial developments with representatives of the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The deputies also discussed the progress of recovery in
economies affected by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank presented a report on the recovery
process in East Asia, saying "recovery has reflected the self-
correcting properties of market economies."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank also reported a favorable economic outlook,
described it as "the strongest in over a decade". It said the APEC
economies have been at the vanguard of this remarkable recovery".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Stocks Fall Slightly, Most Investors on Sidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua)-- Thai stocks drop slightly
Friday, as most investors stay on the sidelines due to lack of
fresh market-moving factors, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index closed down 1.24
point, or 0.4%, at 297.07 points, after moving in a tight range of
298.00 and 300.48.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip SET 50 index is down 0.12 point, or 0.5%, at 20.
72 points. The volume is 105.9 million shares worth 1.8 billion
baht (44 million U.S. dollars). As the index declines, decliners
have outnumbered advancers by 84 to 57, with 87 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Among a handful active stocks, energy shares are closed higher
on expectations they will benefit from rising global oil prices.
</P>
<P>
PTT Exploration &AMP; Production, the largest Thai gas producer,
rose 4, or 1.65 % to 246, has lead the energy sectoral index up 1.
35%.
</P>
<P>
Big energy users such as Thai Airways International Company
decline on investors' concerns that rising jet fuel prices will
erode profit margins. The company fell 1.75, or 4.86% to 34.25.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the market sentiment is still gloomy because of
concerns over the upcoming general elections, due in the fourth
quarter, and rising global oil prices.
</P>
<P>
A dealer at KGI Securities One said there is only some
speculative buying in selected stocks amid a sluggish market.
</P>
</TEXT>
