<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Industry to be Spared by Power Cut in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's industry will be
exempted from the current power rationing by October 20, according
to Kenya Electricity Regulation Board.
</P>
<P>
Consumers at homes will also have something to cheer about as
the rationing eases to the initial minor rationing from last
September to May this year, the East African Standard reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the period, homes and factories had power cuts of 15
hours and 24 hours per week respectively. Since May the rationing
has worsened with a 72-hour blackout per week for residential
areas and 84 hours per week for the industry.
</P>
<P>
The rationing will be eased after three emergency diesel power
generating units reduce the current deficit from 197 megawatts to
50 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
One of the emergency generating units has already commissioned
for the power supply of 45 megawatts. The other two units are
expected to generate 30 megawatts each from October 1.
</P>
<P>
The current power shortage has led to an industrial daily loss
of over 2 million U.S. dollars in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Due to the prolonged drought, the main source of power supply
in Kenya, hydropower stations, have had a low water level and
reduced the generating capacity greatly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
