<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Palestinians are unlikely to declare a state on
Wednesday, as Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
has threatened since the breakdown of the Camp David summit, and
contact between the two sides will continue after that date,
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said at a press conference at the
United Nations on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
His comments come amid a general pessimism among those who
accompanied him to the U.N. Millennium Summit that any breakthrough
is imminent while Barak, Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton are
all in New York. No trilateral meetings are scheduled before Arafat
flies back to Gaza for Saturday's meeting of the Palestinian
National Council.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat told U.
S. President Bill Clinton on Wednesday that he demands Palestinian
sovereignty over the Temple Mount. Arafat said he is unwilling to
discuss the American bridging proposals on Jerusalem that were put
forward during and after the Camp David summit, Israeli sources who
received a report on the meeting, said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of these statements, Clinton decided not to continue
with his mediation efforts between Israel and the Palestinians
during the U.N. Millennium Summit in New York.
</P>
<P>
In the weeks ahead, the United States will try to lead an
international effort aimed at persuading Arafat to demonstrate
flexibility and agree to resume the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- A mistake in the movement of a support unit of the Israeli
elite Duvdevan force which took part in the operation to capture a
member of the Palestinian Islamic militant Hamas group prompted a
series of failures that ended with the death of three soldiers by "
friendly fire," and the wounding of a fourth, according to a
detailed report of the failed action made public by Chief of Staff
Shaul Mofaz Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz also announced that he was accepting the resignations of
the head of the Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) division of the West
Bank, Brigadier General Shlomo Oren, and Lieutenant Colonel "Miki"
and relieved them of their command.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Saying that there will be no whitewash in the Israeli Defense
Forces (IDF), Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz Thursday night accepted
the resignations of two officers who were responsible for the
botched raid in which a senior member of the Palestinian Islamic
Hamas group escaped and three Israeli soldiers were killed by "
friendly fire."
</P>
<P>
He also ordered the implementation of an inquiry's
recommendation that the training of elite units be overhauled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
