<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Economy Expected to Grow Faster in 2000: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Central Bank said the
island's economy is expected to continue to grow at a satisfactory
pace in 2000 and real GDP (gross domestic product) growth is
forecast to reach 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a report published in Friday's local newspapers, the Central
Bank said output growth is expected to be underpinned by a revival
in domestic demand, while foreign demand is envisaged to sustain
its uptrend, enhanced by the performance of the tourist sector.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' gross domestic product expanded by 4.5 percent in real
terms in 1999, when inflation fell to 1.7 percent, the historically
low level.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 annual report said that in 2000, unemployment will
remain at around 3.5 percent, while stricter criteria have been
applied as regards the policy on the employment of foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
But inflation is on the rise, due to the VAT (value added tax)
increase and the soaring fuel price in international markets.
Inflation is provisionally set to rise by 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Import growth is being enhanced by the enlarged fuel bill, as
well as the revival of imports for both home consumption and re-
exports.
</P>
<P>
Net invisible earnings are forecast to widen markedly,
reflecting the continued good performance of tourism and other
exported services, the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals are projected to grow by 10-11 percent while a
further increase in per capita expenditure is also anticipated.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account large net capital inflows, the overall
balance of payments position is forecast to show a deficit of 90
million Cyprus pounds (144 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the public sector deficit in 2000 is
expected to widen to 260.9 million pounds (417.4 million dollars)
or 4.8 percent of GDP, compared to a deficit of 220.8 million
pounds (353.3 million dollars), or 4.5 percent in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
