<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, September 8 Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, Friday, September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG -- The official foreign currency reserve assets of
Hong Kong amounted to 100.4 billion U.S.dollars at the end of
August 2000, compared with 98.9 billion U.S.dollars at end-July,
according to the Hong Kong Monetary Authority Thursday.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
KATHMANDU -- Tourist arrivals in Nepal continue to decline even
after the resumption of India Airlines flights to the country on
June 1 this year, according to Tribhuvan International Airport
Immigration Office.
</P>
<P>
Data issued by the immigration office showed that tourist
arrivals in the country in the first eight months of this year
declined by 13.69 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Worried over soaring global crude prices, which
broke a 10-year record on Wednesday by breaching the 34 U.S.
dollars a barrel mark, India on Thursday urged OPEC nations to
bring down prices to 26 dollars a barrel, the Press Trust of India
(PTI) reported here.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The export value of machinery and electrical
equipment in Beijing reached 1.28 billion U.S. dollars in the
first seven months of this year, up 93.2 percent from the same
period last year, the latest statistics from Beijing Customs show.
</P>
<P>
The import value of such products during the same period
reached 2.94 billion U.S. dollars, increasing 30.5 percent from
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan's exports in August stood at 790 million
U.S. dollars as against 639 million dollars in the same period of
the last year, Minister for Commerce Abdul Razak Dawood said here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
XIAMEN -- China has been the biggest foreign direct investment
recipient of all developing countries for seven years in a row
since 1993, a senior trade official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Fourth China Fair for International Investment
and Trade, which opened Friday, Shi Guangsheng, minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation, said that as of July this
year, China has approved more than 353,000 foreign-invested
enterprises, involving a contractual investment of 641.7 billion U.
S. dollars and actual funds of 327.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
XIAMEN -- China has offered favorable business opportunities to
overseas investors as reforms and opening-up continue and
modernization process picks up speed, State Councilor Wu Yi said
Friday in Xiamen of Southeast China's coastal province of Fujian.
</P>
<P>
In her speech at the luncheon meeting of the Fourth China Fair
for International Investment and Trade, Wu promised that overseas
investment will find enormous potential in such areas as
agriculture, water conservation, energy,communications,
telecommunications, raw materials, environmental protection, high-
tech and important equipment as China continues to implement the
principle and policies of driving domestic demand and facilitates
the strategic readjustment of economic structure.
</P>
<P>
"China is carrying out the strategy of developing the western
region. The industrial base, technical strength and rich natural
and labor resources in the middle and western regions are
favorable conditions for overseas people to participate in the
cooperation and development of these regions," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The Ministry of Information Technology (MIT)
announced Friday that all laser visual disc players and DVD
machines sold in China have to be compatible with the Chinese-
developed technical standard of SVCD.
</P>
<P>
At a working meeting on the technical standard of super video
compact discs or SVCD Friday, Vice Minister of Information
Industry Lu Xinkui said the Chinese-developed SVCD standard has
already been adopted as a universal industrial standard around the
globe by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in
July.
</P>
<P>
He said that this will promote the expansion of Chinese
manufactures both at home and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
