<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Formally Qits COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania ceased to be a member
state of Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA)
effective from mid-night of September 1, 2000, according to a
press release from COMESA headquarters obtained here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, Tanzania has lost all the rights and privileges
it enjoyed by virtue of being a COMESA member state. Goods
originating from Tanzania are no longer eligible for COMESA trade
preferences and are now liable to full national rates of customs
duty in all the COMESA member states, it said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, COMESA Certificates of Origin issued by Tanzania are
immediately null and void.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, goods originating from COMESA member states will not
be accorded COMESA trade preferences by Tanzania, when exported to
that country.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Tanzania is not eligible to use COMESA transit
facilities and instruments, namely the COMESA Customs Document,
the COMESA Customs Bond Guarantee Scheme, and the COMESA Carriers'
License.
</P>
<P>
This means that a Tanzanian licensed truck carrying goods to
any COMESA member state should not be allowed to load and carry
any goods from within COMESA to any destination, after offloading
its cargo.
</P>
<P>
Any Tanzanian licensed trucker violating this condition shall
be liable to penalties prescribed in the COMESA member state where
the offense is committed, which may include seizure and forfeiture
of the truck, it said.
</P>
<P>
COMESA is a regional integration grouping 20 Africa sovereign
states, which have agreed to promote regional integration through
trade development and to develop their natural and human resources
for the mutual benefit of all their people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Officer Nabbed on Suspicion of Passing Secrets to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese police on Friday
arrested a senior officer of Japan's Maritime Self-Defense Force (
MSDF) for allegedly passing defense secrets to a Russian military
attache in Tokyo, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The Metropolitan Police Department (MPD) and Kanagawa
prefectural police arrested Shigehiro Hagisaki, a lieutenant
commander and researcher at the National Institute for Defense
Studies of Japan's Defense Agency, on suspicion of violating the
Self-Defense Forces (SDF) Law, which prohibits SDF members from
divulging classified security information, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Russian Embassy official in Tokyo was quoted by
Itar-Tass news agency as saying that the arrest is a provocation.
</P>
<P>
"We regard the incident as a provocation with the aim to
undermine all positive achievements in the bilateral relations for
the past few years," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The MPD and Kanagawa police raided four locations, including
the institute in Tokyo's Meguro Ward and Hagisaki's home in
Setagaya Ward, seizing several hundred items.
</P>
<P>
Police said Hagisaki gave the Russian military attache
information about the MSDF on about 10 occasions from September
1999 to last month.
</P>
<P>
Hagisaki, 38, basically admitted the allegations, Kyodo quoted
police as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hagisaki was dined and wined in return for handing over
classified documents, and is suspected of receiving money as well,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
After graduating from the National Defense Academy in Yokosuka,
Kanagawa Prefecture, in 1986, Hagisaki served aboard destroyers
and support craft. Fluent in Russian, he had also worked in the
MSDF's documentation division, which deals with information on
foreign defense.
</P>
<P>
Hagisaki had been working at the institute as an expert on
Russia since the end of March this year after completing a master'
s course on security at the academy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
