<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Vessel Saved near Chinese Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A Democratic People's Republic
of Korea boat with over 100 persons on board has been rescued near
northeast China's city of Dandong after drifting at sea for four
days, China's State Maritime Administration (SMA) said today.
</P>
<P>
A DPRK ship is now on its way to tow the powerless flat-
bottomed boat, now anchored safely in DPRK waters, the SMA said.
</P>
<P>
According to SMA officials, a Chinese ship called "Zhehai 314"
discovered the DPRK pontoon at 11:20 a.m. Thursday about 20
nautical miles south of Dandong on its way from Pusan of the
Republic of Korea, when its crew saw many people on the pontoon
waving their clothes.
</P>
<P>
"Zhehai 314" soon approached the DPRK vessel and reported the
situation to the China Maritime Rescue Center (CMRC), as a
language barrier prevented them from taking further action.
</P>
<P>
Another nearby Chinese vessel identified as "Honghu 8" was soon
dispatched to the area by the CMRC, whose crew was told that the
DPRK boat had been drifting at sea when the cable connecting it
with a tug boat broke and the ship stranded four days ago.
</P>
<P>
When efforts to contact the DPRK maritime authority failed, the
DPRK pontoon was tugged to waters near a DPRK island and anchored
there. The two Chinese ships left after making sure that the DPRK
boat and the people on board were safe.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK side was eventually informed of the situation by
Dandong port authorities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Candle" Libraries Built in Rural Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China will build 300 "candle"
libraries for rural primary schools in the provinces of Gansu and
Sichuan in west China by the country's 16th Teacher's Day, which
falls Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Chinese Charity Federation (CCF) said that
these libraries will help enrich rural students' knowledge and
improve rural teachers' professional levels.
</P>
<P>
To celebrate this year's Teacher's Day, CCF and the McDonald
Food Ltd. Corporation jointly held an activity called the "Candle
Library Project."
</P>
<P>
The activity, which began in July, has collected books and
donations in a bid to establish libraries for primary schools in
poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
To narrow the education gap between rural and urban schools,
organizers call for more people to participate in the Candle
Library Project and other public welfare undertakings.
</P>
<P>
By September 6, about 400,000 books had been donated from
cities like, Beijing, Tianjin, Taiyuan, Qingdao, Jinan, Zibo,
Shenyang, Dalian, Anshan, Harbin, Jilin and Changchun. The books
will be placed in Candle libraries.
</P>
<P>
Initiated in 1998 by CCF, the Candle Project aims to lessen the
burden of teachers in poor rural schools and improve their
professional levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
