<HEADLINE> Manila Stocks End Marginally Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Share prices in the Philippine
Stock Exchange ended marginally higher Friday despite the peso's
continued weakness.
</P>
<P>
The 30-company Phisix, the market's main index, closed 65 of a
point higher to close at 1,523.69. But the broader all-shares
index dropped 6.14 points to 697.42.
</P>
<P>
Dealers exchanged 310 million shares worth some 20.8 million U.
S. dollars on Friday against Thursday's 323.5 million shares worth
some 33.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the market failed to strongly move higher as
investors positioned selectively in blue chip issues on concerns
over the peso volatility.
</P>
<P>
"The character of buying is short-term, that is why the market
only moved sideways. The only thing that perked it up are blue
chip stocks," said Joey Roxas, president of Eagle Securities Inc.
</P>
<P>
The peso averaged 45.607 pesos against the U.S. dollar early
Friday, weaker compared to the previous close of 45.530 pesos.
</P>
