<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's NGO Calls for Registration of Cornea Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- An eye care and protection non-
governmental organization has called for potential cornea donors to
register at local hospitals to facilitate cornea donations in
Jordan, the semi-official Jordan Times reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Friends of Jordan Eye Bank and Prevention of Blindness
Society urged donors to register with their identification cards,
driving licenses or health insurance cards, to be included into a
data bank at Al Bashir Hospital, King Hussein Medical Center and
Jordan University Hospital, the three largest public hospitals of
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Since the cornea bank's founding in 1979, some 14,000 Jordanians
have registered as potential cornea donors, but the availability of
corneas proved to be limited for patients awaiting transplant in
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 to 150 cornea transplant operations are performed in
the kingdom each year while patients on the waiting list stand at
some 2,000, said Nafez Khader, an official with the cornea bank.
</P>
<P>
The new registration mechanism of potential cornea donors will
help hospitals provide patients awaiting a cornea transplant
immediately and spare doctors from asking for permission from the
deceased person's family members, Khader said.
</P>
<P>
The corneas from the deceased are only usable for transplant
within hours after his or her death.
</P>
<P>
The cost of a cornea transplant at public hospitals of the
kingdom stands at 600 to 700 Jordanian dinars (840 to 980 U.S.
dollars), while the price could be up to 2,000 dinars (2,800
dollars) in private hospitals which import corneas from foreign
countries at higher prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
