<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colleges in Cyprus to Merge into Private University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Two leading colleges in Cyprus,
the Cyprus College and the Frederick Institute of Technology, will
join forces to form a non-profit private university.
</P>
<P>
The Weekly newspaper reported Friday that Cyprus College Dean
Andreas Eleftheriades has confirmed the two colleges had reached an
agreement to form a private university, in line with such
institution in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Eleftheriades said as soon as government regulations are ready
by the end of the year for private universities, work will begin
for the new university.
</P>
<P>
The new university will operate in the present buildings of the
two colleges which will gradually operate as a single unity.
</P>
<P>
"All surplus profits from the new university will remain in the
university for further expansion and not go into the owners' hands,
that's why it will be a non-profit private university, according to
the American model," said Eleftheriades.
</P>
<P>
The new university will offer courses to at least 3,000
students, including 13 different Bachelor's degrees and 33
diplomas, covering the entire tertiary education spectrum on the
island.
</P>
<P>
The boards of directors of the two colleges hope the new
university will be a unique opportunity for local and foreign
students.
</P>
<P>
There is so far one university in government-controlled Cyprus -
- the state-run Cyprus University. 
</P>
</TEXT>
