<HEADLINE> Zambia Vows to Host OAU Summit Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian chief government
spokesmen Newstead Zimba has dismissed claims by opposition
parties that it was unnecessary for the country to host the
Organization for African Unity (OAU) summit next year.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Friday quoted Zimba as saying in a statement
issued here on Thursday that politicians, who were against hosting
the meeting in name of the whole country's interest, actually held
their own petty domestic ambitions, which should not be allowed to
derail the government intention meant to benefit the nation.
</P>
<P>
Sakwiba Sikota, second vice president of the opposition United
Party for National Development, reportedly said that it was
unnecessary and costly for Zambia to spend 250 billion kwacha (
about 83 million U.S. dollars) in a year when presidential and
general elections would also be held.
</P>
<P>
Zimba said the figure quoted was a fabrication which did not
exist in the government program.
</P>
<P>
He said member states of the OAU voted for and invited Zambia
to host the summit as a clear testimony of their trust and
confidence in the country.
</P>
<P>
"It should not be forgotten that Zambia is one of the pioneers
in the restoration of multi-party politics on the continent of
Africa," Zimba said, adding: "Within the OAU, Zambia has been one
of the few countries that has advocated sanctions against those
heads of state that come to power through unconstitutional means
from attending OAU meetings."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the spokesman said with about 3,000 delegates
attending the summit, private consumer demand would surely
increase. 
</P>
