<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP to Redirect Food Aid for Human Development in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
would redirect its food aid to promote human development in
Bangladesh, outgoing WFP representative Werner Kiene told The
Independent newspaper here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We want to explore projects with a view to investing in human
capital. We hope that the government can go along the same line
and utilize food aid and assistance in a better way and implement
programs by integrating the interests of the poor people," the WFP
representative said.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the newspaper, Kiene said the
WFP and other U.N. agencies now look forward to an area-based
approach to development as a complement to the sector-based
approach pursued so far.
</P>
<P>
He said that international food donors want to give less
emphasis on infrastructure projects if they do not integrate the
poor, because otherwise they do not directly benefit them in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
The WFP will decentralize its activities by locating some of
its staff to areas most prone to food scarcity at times of stress,
Kiene said.
</P>
<P>
Thirty million ultra poor people are not a problem, but a
potential productive resource that the society can use efficiently.
Once they graduate from poverty, they will be a big group of
consumers and a lot of economic activities will be there centering
on them, the WFP official observed, stressing that human
development should be combined with a policy of inclusion of these
people as equal members of the society.
</P>
<P>
In future, the WFP would distribute a new protein and vitamin
rich food instead of distributing wheat, with a view to helping
improve the nutritional status of the recipients of food aid.
</P>
<P>
The WFP representative said the WFP was increasingly becoming
involved with nutrition and would contribute to the National
Nutrition Program of the Bangladeshi government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Replaces Los Angeles As U.S. Smoggiest City  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A series of sweltering
days and soaring ozone levels pushed Houston ahead of Los Angeles
for the title of the nation's smoggiest city.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that Houston recorded its ninth
consecutive day with an ozone reading above the national health
standard Wednesday, giving Houston 37 high-ozone days for the year,
compared with 34 for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
"High pressure dictates stagnant air. You have no clouds and no
wind," said Steve Allen, a National Weather Service meteorologist.
"The pollutants that are there are going to stay there. You cook
them every day with the sun, and you get a lot of ozone." he added.
</P>
<P>
Houston hit 107 degrees on August 31 and September 1, and on
Monday, the city hit a record-high 109.
</P>
<P>
Thunderstorms pushed inland from the Gulf of Mexico late
Thursday and Friday, which could break the heat and the string of
ozone days, perhaps handing the lead back to Los Angeles, said
Chuck Roeseler, another weather service meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
In Southern California, the final week of August and first few
weeks of September are historically the smoggiest of the year,
according to experts who pointed out that in Houston smog season
lasts much longer, sometimes beginning in February and persisting
as late as November.
</P>
<P>
They also say that much of Los Angeles' ozone is formed when
exhaust from cars and smokestacks released during the day mixes
with other chemicals and sunshine, while in Houston much of the
pollution comes from oil refineries, petrochemical plants and
cargo ships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000908.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Runner Killed in Accident in Southern Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- One week away from the opening
of the millieum Olympics, a Nigerian runner was killed in a
traffic accident in Southern Australia.
</P>
<P>
Hyginus Anugo, 22, a middle distance runner who competed in the
World Junior Championships in 1996 in Sydney, was hit by a car as
he crossed a street Thursday night, the official Olympic News
Service said.
</P>
<P>
Local television said Anugo was killed while running to catch a
bus.
</P>
<P>
John Coates, president of the Australian Olympic Committee,
said Anugo did not have Olympic accreditation and was not staying
at the Olympic athletes' village.
</P>
<P>
Anugo was with the team in Adelaide where final selections for
relay squads were made. Anugo was not selected after failing to
finish in the top six in a recent team trial.
</P>
<P>
In a condolence note, IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch on
Friday "expressed his sympathy and expressed the sympathy of the
IOC to the national Olympic committee of Nigeria and the family of
the athlete who was killed tragically last night," said IOC
director general Francois Carrard. 
</P>
