<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Members Asked to Reduce Share Holdings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The National Counter
Corruption Commission of Thailand (NCCC) on Friday asked cabinet
members to reduce their share holdings in any company to no more
than 5 percent before November 9.
</P>
<P>
The request is based on the Cabinet Members' Business
Partnership and Shareholding Management Act of 2000, written in
line with Article 209 of the Constitution, aimed at "preventing
conflict of interest involving cabinet members."
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members who want to hold on to shares in excess of the
limit are required to notify the NCCC and to transfer those shares
to the care of a trust, it said.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members have been required to include details about
their share holdings in their financial status report to the NCCC,
it said,and will be sued at the Constitution Court if they conceal
information about their share holdings.
</P>
<P>
According to Article 216 of the Constitution, if found guilty
by the Constitution Court, violators will lose their governmental
status and face possible imprisonment of between one and ten years,
the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
The NCCC also plans to put information about cabinet members'
assets and liabilities on a government website, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
