<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Police Caution Ministers of Possible Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Inspector General
of Police Lucky Kodituwakku has cautioned cabinet ministers of the
possibility of assassination attempts on them by Tamil Tiger
rebels in the run-up to the general elections on October 10, press
reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The police chief was quoted by the private Island as saying
that operatives of separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (
LTTE) had visited the residences of some of the ministers as part
of their effort to gather information about the ministers.
</P>
<P>
In a move to beef up security for the ministers, the government
last month imported several bullet-proof cars for senior ministers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kodituwakku Thursday canceled leave for all police
officers. He told the ranks that they would not be allowed to take
leave in the run up to the elections amid fears of more poll-
related violence and LTTE's assassination attempts.
</P>
<P>
At least five people have been killed in election-related
violence since the parliament was dissolved on August 18. The
campaign began earlier this week after nominations closed for the
11th parliamentary general elections.
</P>
<P>
Security has also been tightened for the Sri Lankan Prime
Minister Ratnasiri Wickremanayake as he is believed to be a prime
target of LTTE rebels who have in the past assassinated several
Sri Lankan leaders.
</P>
<P>
Wickremanayake has been given presidential security division
cover as he is expected to lead the ruling People's Alliance
government's campaign for the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE is fighting a 17-year war against majority Sinhalese
dominated government in a bid to carve out a separate state for
minority Tamils in the country's north and east.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE attacked both government and opposition rallies during
last December's presidential elections campaign killing dozens of
people and seriously wounding President Kumaratunga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
