<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Soar Beyond Control: Thailand Petroleum Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Petroleum Authority of
Thailand (PTT) warned that the continued rise in world oil prices
has gone beyond its ability to effectively keep the lid on
domestic prices, The Nation reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
PTT governor Viset Choopiban was quoted as saying that if world
oil prices rose again, the PTT would have no choice but to raise
local oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Viset said that since July, the PTT had spent 700 million baht
(17 million U.S. dollars) to keep local oil prices from rising too
much.
</P>
<P>
The price of crude oil in the world market hit a 10-year high
Thursday, reaching nearly 35 dollar a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The price of diesel oil, in particular, could go up further in
the near future due to growing demand for heating oil in western
countries during the winter, Viset said.
</P>
<P>
The PTT just allowed the local diesel oil price to increase by
another 0.30 baht (0.7 cent) a liter Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"If other oil companies increase the price, we will have to
follow suit. Nevertheless, we will keep our diesel price 0.30 baht
(0.7 cent) a liter cheaper than others," the PTT governor said.
</P>
<P>
The organization has been losing 1.1 baht (2.6 cents) a liter
on diesel and 0.4 baht (0.9 cent) a liter on various petrol
products, he said.
</P>
<P>
Science, Technology and Environment Minister Pornthep Tejapibul
was quoted as saying that he would propose that the National
Energy Policy Committee (NEPO) cut the tax on oil products by one
baht (2.4 cent) a liter to help soften local oil prices.
</P>
<P>
He said the government could make up the lost revenue by
suppressing oil smuggling, which would lead to higher oil sales.
</P>
<P>
Governor Viset said NEPO had agreed to an oil tax cut as a last
resort. He pointed out that now would be a suitable time for a cut
as the country had run out of alternatives to deal with the price
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
