<HEADLINE> Thai Senate Begins Deliberating Election Law Amendment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Thai Senate begins to
deliberate the election law amendment bill here Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has urged the 200-seat Senate to give a
speedy passage of the bill, which has been endorsed by the House
of Representatives, the lower house, on August 31, to ensure that
the upcoming general election will be held under the amended law.
</P>
<P>
The lower house's term ends on November 17, but a dissolution
seems sure to happen before that date, and the general election
will then be called, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
However, during discussions in Friday morning, many senators
said they could not pass a bill that puts the independent Election
Commission under a screening panel under the government, which is
proposed and endorsed by the House.
</P>
<P>
This means the Senate will possibly push for changes in the
amendment bill to give the Election Commission absolute power to
handle the election, including disqualification of candidates.
</P>
<P>
The Senate will vote for a decision after debates within
several days.
</P>
<P>
Once the changes are made by the Senate, the bill will be
returned to the House, and then the two houses of the parliament
will form a joint committee to work on the bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
