<HEADLINE> U.S. University Workers Stage Sickout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of workers at the
University of Texas continued a sickout Thursday saying they are
tired of what they call unfair working conditions at the state's
largest university.
</P>
<P>
The non-teaching employees are seeking pay raises, including an
hourly minimum of 9.16 dollars, and want their insurance premiums
to remain unchanged, according to reports reaching here late
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The university has said it was forced to raise premiums to
offset rising insurance costs. Workers earning 30,000 dollars a
year or less were given a 50-dollar-a-month raise to help offset
the increases.
</P>
<P>
University operations were normal Thursday, the second day of
the three-day work disruption, said Pat Clubb, the vice president
of employee and campus operations.
</P>
<P>
About 300 students rallied and some professors held classes off
campus to show their support for the workers.
</P>
<P>
Exactly how many of the school's 17,000 non-teaching employees
stayed home would not be available for several days. Clubb
estimated the number would be about 500. The University Staff
Association said about 4,800 workers agreed to participate.
</P>
<P>
The sickout at University of Texas followed a similar one
Tuesday at Eastern Michigan University, where more than 650
professors went on strike for salary and benefit increases.
</P>
<P>
Salaries for full professors at Eastern Michigan University
averaged 63,000 dollars in 1998-99, according to the latest
figures available from the Mid-American Conference. The average in
the conference, which represents 12 comparable public universities,
was 68,000 dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
