<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Makes Efforts to Bring Down Illiteracy Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar makes efforts to bring
down its illiteracy rate to 9 percent this year from 21.4 percent
in 1983, according to Friday's official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The paper attributed this to the Education for All Program.
</P>
<P>
The literacy rate in Myanmar has reached 91 percent and
endeavors are being made for the remaining 9 percent to be
literates in the 21st century, the paper said hailing the
International Literacy Day which falls on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In its efforts to turn illiterates into literates under the
basic literacy program, Myanmar, along with 12 other nations in
Asia and the Pacific region, established in March this year the
Literacy Resources Center (LRC) in cooperation with the Asia
Pacific Cultural Center (LRC) for U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
The LRC is to undertake the tasks of production of teaching
aids, literacy training and communication networks with non-
governmental organizations at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Myanmar is also making efforts to enable neo-literates
to be life-long learners under the reading skills promotion
programs and become members of learning society in the knowledge
age of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's illiteracy rate declined to 57 percent from 65
percent after regaining independence in 1948 due to first attempt
of public education and making new life through education from
1948 to 1964.
</P>
<P>
From 1964 to 1983, the country's literacy mass movement was
launched for the second time with illiteracy rate decreasing to 21.
4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
