<HEADLINE> Croatia Approves Landmine Clearing Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Croatian government
recently approved a 10-year landmine clearing program Thursday,
Croatian radio and television station reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the program aims to remove all
landmines in the country by 2010. It will cost 9.6 billion kuna (1.
14 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government believes the program's cost will place too great
a strain on national finances. So, the government is now seeking
alternative funding sources, including credit from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Landmines Removal Center estimates that around one
million landmines are buried beneath over 500 square kilometers of
land. The landmines were planted during the civil war from 1990 to
1995. 
</P>
