<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Arrested Over U.N. Staff Murder in West Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen suspects have been
arrested for their suspected involvement in Wednesday's attack
against civilian U.N. staff in the border town of Atambua, West
Timor, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security
Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono said he had received word on the
arrests from the Udayana Regional Military Command Chief Major
General Kiki Syahnakri.
</P>
<P>
"The team of investigation has already begun work and 15 people
are being questioned," he was quoted by the Indonesian Observer
Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The investigation team consisted of five police officers from
the provincial headquarters and five soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the killing of the three U.N. humanitarian
workers could have been political.
</P>
<P>
"We are investigating whether it was triggered by the death (of
a militiaman) or caused by political motives to discredit the
government," Susilo said.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place after Olivio Mendoza Moruk, former
chief of a pro-Jakarta East Timorese militia group, was found
beheaded in his home Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, at least three staff members of the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) were killed when an angry
mob of pro-Jakarta East Timorese or so-called militia launched an
armed attack on the representatives office of the UNHCR in Atambua,
a city in Indonesia's East Nusa Tenggara province.
</P>
<P>
Susilo said he had instructed security authorities in West
Timor to immediately work to halt the violence and prevent it from
spreading and to assure and protect the security of foreigners,
including UNHCR staff remaining in Atambua.
</P>
<P>
He said extra troops would be sent in and insisted Indonesia
forces had done their best to stop the tragic event.
</P>
<P>
In New York, President Abdurrahman Wahid, who is now attending
a U.N. millennium conference, claimed the attack had been
engineered by his political opponents to undercut international
support for his reforms.
</P>
<P>
"This was done at a time when I am in New York, at the United
Nations, in order to embarrass me," the president was quoted by
the Antara News Agency Friday as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
