<HEADLINE> World Bank to Reduce Poor Countries' Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank's primary task
for the remaining year is to cut 30 billion U.S. dollars in debts
owed by 20 poor countries, said a World Bank official at a press
conference here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Francois Rischard, vice president for Europe of the World
Bank, said there are 35 countries across the globe where emergency
aid is badly needed.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Rischard said, the theme of the annual meeting in
Prague this month by the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund is "Poverty and Debt Exemption and Reduction."
</P>
<P>
Participants will discuss at the meeting world financial
stability and economic development. The meeting will also discuss
for the first time such issues as global climatic changes,
decreasing forest coverage and organized international crime.
</P>
<P>
One third of World Bank funds come from Europe, Rischard said,
adding that European countries, therefore, will play an increasing
important role in providing material aid to under-developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Experience and lessons learned in the last decade bear witness
to the fact that the World Bank should attach greater importance
to developing countries in terms of their governmental
administration and related systems, in addition to granting aid to
cultural, educational and public health sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
