<HEADLINE> Colombia's Damaged Pipelines Resume Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Two pipelines in Colombia have
resumed operation after experiencing numerous attacks by guerrilla
groups, Colombian Petroleum Company (Ecopetrol) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 700-kilometer long Cano Limon-Covenas pipeline, the second
largest in Colombia, renewed pumping 250,000 barrels of oil per
day, after being inactive for 45 days, said the company.
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas from the National Liberation Army (ELN) and
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) carried out 24
attacks against pipelines in 40 days, preventing the pumping of 4.
7 million barrels of export oil.
</P>
<P>
This is the longest suspension of operations of the pipeline
since 1986, when production of Cano Limon began.
</P>
<P>
Oil is the main export product of Colombia. For the year 2000,
income has been calculated at five billion U.S. dollars, involving
about 35 percent of the total exports, but due to intensifying
guerrilla attacks, this figure will probably be lower.
</P>
<P>
The ELN, Colombia's second largest guerrilla force, responsible
for the greatest number of attacks against oil and electricity
infrastructures, warned that sabotage will continue until the
government has a new nationalist energy policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
