<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science to Uncover Doping in Sydney: S. African Professor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the National
Olympic Committee of South Africa's (NOCSA's) anti-doping
commission Winton Hawksworth Thursday predicted that doping will
be a big factor at this month's Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the top athletes in the world will test positive at
the Games because of the scientific advances since last Olympics,"
said Hawksworth, a retired professor of chemistry, who also sits
on the medical commission of the International Sailing Federation
and international swimming's doping control review board.
</P>
<P>
He further contended that the International Olympic Committee's
decision this week to introduce a combined blood-uring dope test
for erthropoietin (EPO), which stimulates the production of red
blood cells and provides fuel for the muscles, will doom those
athletes who thought such a test will not be approved in time for
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Hawksworth believed South Africa will have a clean team in
Sydney,although anyone crafty enough to have avoided detection,
particularly for the use of stamina-boosting EPO, will be found
out once the doctors come round with their own syringes to take
blood.
</P>
<P>
"The damage to national prestige would be immense," warned the
professor, adding: " The health issue is another story, but the
fact that an athlete is a cheat would be terrible."
</P>
<P>
Hawksworth has spent the past two years primarily educating
South Africa's potential Olympians on NOCSA's policy towards
doping.
</P>
<P>
In this time only two athletes, a boxer and a cyclist, were
excluded from consideration because they tested positive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
