<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Military Service Law Due For Drastic Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Following years of debate
over Chile's Obligatory Military Service (OMS) law, the government
has proposed a series of important changes in the way youth are
recruited for military service, the local newspaper "La Tercera"
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The changes, announced on Tuesday by President Ricardo Lagos,
include automatic inscription for young people on their 18th
birthday, semi-voluntary service, increased participation by women
and greater incentives for recruits, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"These changes involve greater expense for the state as well as
significant legal reforms and therefore will be implemented
gradually beginning next year and concluding in 2005," Lagos said.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Defense Minister Mario Fernandez will be responsible
for formalizing the proposed changes to the OMS, a task that must
be completed in the next 90 days.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez said the first change to be implemented will be the
automatic registration of young people on their 18th birthday.
This reform, which will be instituted in 2001, will replace the
current process that requires young people to appear in person at
recruitment centers to register for military service.
</P>
<P>
"(This change) will eliminate the entire recruiting process as
well as the sanctions for failing to register. This is currently
an enormous administrative and judicial problem because young
people who do not register are subject to disciplinary action, and
there are close to 10,000 such cases per year," Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
Another change soon to come will be the increased emphasis on
voluntary conscription. In 1998, 53 percent of those who completed
the OMS did so by choice, a figure that increased to 68 percent in
1999. The government hopes to attract even more voluntary recruits
by creating financial incentives, including a substantial increase
in monthly salaries, scholarships for higher education and links
with businesses to ensure work for recruits after they complete
their military service.
</P>
<P>
"We have some job training and also some educational
opportunities at lower levels, but these apply only to a small
fraction of conscripts who make use of the services. The measures
that we are going to take now are much wider in scope," Fernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
In the event that the military quota is not filled by voluntary
conscripts, a draft will be held to fill the remaining vacancies.
Those who are chosen will be required to complete their military
service unless they meet specified exemption requirements, which
have not yet been defined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
