<HEADLINE> "I Am as Clean as Snow", Says Konchellah  By Sun Huixia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- 800 meters runner Patrick
Konchellah, One of Kenya's main medal hopes in the Sydney Olympics,
Thursday denied that his withdrawal from the Games was linked with
the fear of a possible blood test.
</P>
<P>
"I want to make it clear that I withdrew because of stomach
complications," Konchellah told Xinhua after returning to Kenya's
capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
He said that he did not run away from Sydney and he was not
hiding either.
</P>
<P>
"I am available here in Nairobi now for testing even by the
IAAF (International Amateur Athletic Federation). I was tested
four times this year, two in Europe and two in Kenya, and all the
results were negative," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am as clean as snow," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked why he refused to be attended by Kenyan Olympic team
doctors in Australia, he said that he had some medicine with him
and he was also worried that maybe the treatment by the doctors
would worsen his health.
</P>
<P>
Konchellah, who arrived in Nairobi on Wednesday morning and was
due to leave soon for his base in The Hague, Holland, said that he
started developing stomach pains when he came back to Kenya a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
When answering the possible causes of the pain, he blamed the
mixture of food and water he ate in Nairobi after back from Europe.
</P>
<P>
"I was very sick in Sydney and in a terrible condition. In the
past two weeks I could not meet the daily training schedules," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"But I am fine now and you can see me here talking. But the
state is not good enough for the Olympic games and even if the
pain eases," he said vigorously after talking about 40 minutes
with the press.
</P>
<P>
After consulting with his private doctor in Nairobi, he
presented a letter on a pull-out to Kenya Amateur Athletic
Association on August 30 and got the approval four days later.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that Kenya will do well in the games and added
that he will fly to Sydney on September 25 to watch the 800 meters
final and give the three Kenyans moral support.
</P>
<P>
"Kenyans have a clean record regarding drug abuse. I personally
believe that all Kenyans athletes to Sydney are clean," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am of course very sad, but it is part of life," he said when
commenting his decision. "Next Olympic Games is still far away, I
can not say anything about my chance in four years."
</P>
<P>
His best performance for the 800-meter event is one minute 42
seconds 98 while the current world record is one minute 41 seconds
11.
</P>
<P>
Kenya media has speculated that Konchellah quitted possibly due
to links with performance enhancing drugs on the grounds that he
refused to be treated by Kenyan Olympic team doctors.
</P>
<P>
Around 38 Kenyan athletes are set to take part in the track and
field events in Sydney and Kenyan National Olympic Committee has
predicted a harvest of at least four gold medals and six to eight
silver and bronze.  
</P>
</TEXT>
