<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets With U.S. President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
met here Friday with U.S. President Bill Clinton and exchanged
with him views over the bilateral relations and major regional and
world issues of common concern, a Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang, who is here to attend the U.N. Millennium
summit, said that China and the United States, as the two big
powers in the world, have born the common historical
responsibility for the cause of promoting world peace and
development.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the past years the general trend of the Sino-U.
S. ties, though experiencing ups and downs, have steadily moved
forward. Facts have proven that to keep and develop a healthy and
steady relationship between the two nations is not only in the
fundamental interests of both peoples, but also beneficial to the
peace, stability and development in the Asian-Pacific region and
the world as a whole, Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang pointed out that at the turn of the century,
the governments and leaders of the two countries should stand
ascending and firmly hold the general situation of the bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
The two sides should, on the basis of the three Sino-U.S. joint
communiques, expand exchanges and cooperation and appropriately
handle the differences and Taiwan issue in particular so as to
keep the Sino-U.S. relations developing forward healthily,
steadily and continuously in the new century, which is beneficial
to the peace, stability, development and prosperity of the world,
the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton said that the United States and China have
had a good cooperation over the past eight years since he took
office, and leaders of the two nations have personally pushed
forward the improvement and development of the bilateral ties,
increased exchanges and made their efforts in winning the support
of their people for developing the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said that the U.S. side sincerely hoped that the
two nations would realize true cooperation and China would succeed
in its economic and social construction.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang elaborate China's principle position on the
Taiwan issue, saying that "we have said many times as long as the
Taiwan authorities recognize the one China principle, the contacts
and dialogues between the two sides across the straits can be
restored, leader of Taiwan can come to the mainland or we could go
to Taiwan for talks and anything can be discussed."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president said that his country would continue to
abide by the one-China policy, hoping that the Taiwan issue could
be solved peacefully.
</P>
<P>
On the question of U.S. permanent normal trade relations (PNTR)
with China, Jiang said that an early realization of PNTR is
beneficial to the expansion of economic and trade cooperation
between the two nations and to the long-term healthy and steady
development of bilateral relations as well, which benefits the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the U.S. Administration is striving hard for
the passing by the Senate of the PNTR bill and the review in the
Senate has made progress, believing that the issue could be solved
soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
