<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Tourists Visit Romania in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2.35 million
tourists visited Romania in the first six months of 2000, up 7.4
percent from the same period of the previous year, the official
Rompres news agency Friday quoted data of the Tourism Promotion
Office as showing.
</P>
<P>
Most tourists, 2.25 million, came from European countries. They
are followed by Asian tourists (53,687) and North American ones (
39,213).
</P>
<P>
As regards European tourists, they came mostly from the
Republic of Moldova, Hungary, Bulgaria, Ukraine, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The maximum increase of the number of arrivals in Romania was
registered for the tourists from Portugal (32.9 percent), Norway (
28.5 percent) and France (25.2 percent) as compared with the first
six months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, a growth by 8 percent in the number of
foreign visitors in Romania was registered in 1999.
</P>
<P>
After an absence of a decade from the maps of the great
European tourist destinations, Romania returned to the attention
of foreign countries, mainly during the past year, after tourism
promotion programs which publicized the total solar eclipse in the
summer of 1999, as well as passing into a new millennium, the
ultimate purpose being to attract foreign tourists from the
countries regarded as targets for the message.
</P>
<P>
All these were materialized during a severe decline of Romania'
s returns from tourism, which amounted to about 250 million U.S.
dollars in 1999, as against 590 million U.S. dollars in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
