<HEADLINE> Romania Launches Euro Bonds in Comeback on Foreign Capital Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 8 (Xinhua) -- After three years, Romania
has returned on the international capital market with bonds worth
300 million euros, matured within seven and ten years respectively,
the Rompres news agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new series of bonds will be traded by ING Barings of the
Netherlands, which hopes to make the transaction complete by the
end of October, 2000.
</P>
<P>
"It may seem a risky move on the eve of elections, but the wide
political consensus for European integration has altered the
Romanian political landscape. I don't see any reason why the new
series of bonds would not be successful," said Stan Rudcenko, an
economist at SG Securities.
</P>
<P>
Romania last year made an abortive attempt to come up on the
capital international market, at the insistence of the
International Monetary Fund, which subsequently gave up the
condition that Romania had to earn funds from private lenders and
thus offered Romanian authorities more flexibility in financing
matters.
</P>
<P>
Merryll Lynch, ING Barings, Dresdner Bank and Morgan Stanley
have now been interested in offering the Romanian government soft
loans and advantageous return deadlines.
</P>
<P>
The reserves of Romania's central bank stand at about 2.1
billion U.S. dollars, an indication that the bank will not default
on its foreign payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
