<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Method to Genetically Modify Pigs is Efficient, Expert Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The method developed in Italy to
genetically modify pigs in order to produce organs which can be
transplanted into humans is the most efficient and economic in the
world today, researchers said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The claim came from Mariluisa Lavitrano, the head of the
genetic transplant project at Rome's La Sapienza University,
during the conference on Bionics for Promoting Man in the Third
Millennium, organized in the framework of the Jubilee for
Universities.
</P>
<P>
Up until now, human genes have been introduced into the genetic
code of pigs by injecting them into the ovary. The method
developed at La Sapienza, on the other hand, injects the human
genes directly into the sperm.
</P>
<P>
Thus the DNA is modified before fertilization and this,
Lavitrano explained, "has proved to be ten times more efficient
than the techniques used so far."
</P>
<P>
The gene injected into the pig's DNA, both in the traditional
method and the one developed in Rome, produces the DAF (decay
accelerating factor) protein which is important for blocking hyper-
acute rejection, the first of the three phases which lead to the
rejection of organs and which takes place in the first minutes
after the transplant.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Lavitrano observed, the path towards
transplanting animal organs into human remains a long one and
extreme caution is necessary, especially after it was discovered
that organs from pigs can also transmit harmful viruses to man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
