<HEADLINE> Main European Stock Markets End Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Europe's main stock markets
fell Friday as earning worries sent Wall Street lower and stoked
fears on both sides of the Atlantic that high oil prices and a
weak euro would crimp profits.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index lost ground steadily through the week
to end Friday's session at 6,600.7 points, down 194.3 points or 2.
9 percent from last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Oil companies weakened ahead of this weekend's OPEC meeting in
Vienna. The powerful oil organization is expected to increase oil
output to try to ease crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
BP Amoco slipped 1.4 percent and Shell Transport and Trading
dropped more than 1 percent. Oil producers benefit from higher
prices for crude oil, although their refining subsidiaries suffer
badly.
</P>
<P>
Technology and telecom stocks fell. Vodafone AirTouch, the
world's biggest mobile phone operator, fell 2.4 percent, BT
slipped 1.3 percent and business telecom operator Colt Telecom
shed 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's Xetra Dax index shed 105.57 points, 1.43 percent,
to 7,267.77, with chemicals firm Bayer sliding 3.4 percent and its
rival BASF slipping 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip CAC 40 in Paris dropped more than 1.9 percent, or
131.1 points, to 6,703.36, with Air Liquide sliding 6.4 percent.
</P>
