<HEADLINE> Wireless Gaming Explosion Forecast in U.S., Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The wireless games
industry in the United States and Europe will grow from nothing
now to a market of 6 billion U.S. dollars by 2005, said a forecast
report released this week.
</P>
<P>
According to the report from Datamonitor, a global market
analysis firm, mobile phones will be the next platform to emerge
for playing games. By 2005, 200 million people in Western Europe
and the U.S. will be playing Internet games on their mobile phones,
representing four out of five mobile users.
</P>
<P>
Western Europe will take a strong lead over the U.S., with the
U.K. and Germany as its largest wireless gaming markets. Five
years from now, Datamonitor predicts that Western Europe will
continue to lead and account for more than 50 percent of wireless
gaming revenues. The U.S. will gradually catch up and by 2005, its
revenues will have risen to 2.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Card games, quiz games, bingo and other classic games will be
the most popular games on mobile phones, according to the study.
Their simplicity and mass appeal will be ideal for the wireless
gaming market. Popular PC and console games will also be gradually
ported onto mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
How will industry players make money out of this market?
According to Datamonitor, sponsorship will be the most lucrative
revenue stream. Content sponsored by third parties or dependent on
customers paying a nominal fee could also prove successful with
the public. Meanwhile, subscriptions will find a receptive
audience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
