<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millennium Summit Ends With Adoption of Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The three-day U.N.
Millennium Summit concluded on Friday evening at the U.N.
headquarters in New York with the adoption of a declaration.
</P>
<P>
The summit, co-chaired by President of Namibia Sam Nujoma,
whose country held the presidency of the 54th session of the
United Nations General Assembly, and President of Finland Tarja
Halone, whose country holds the presidency of the 55th session of
the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The summit, under the official theme "The United Nations in the
21st Century," attracted more than 160 heads of state or
government, the largest-ever gathering of the world's leaders in U.
N. history.
</P>
<P>
The world leaders discussed the world's most pressing problems
including how to pull millions of people out of abject poverty,
strengthen the United Nations in the 21 century, protect the
global environment and reverse the HIV/AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
In addition to making formal speeches at the summit, the world
leaders also participated in one of four interactive round tables
with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's millennium report as the
main topic.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, a meeting of the U.N. Security Council at
the heads of state level and a summit of permanent members of the
security council were also held, focusing on U.N. peacekeeping
operations, especially in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the U.N. chief's call, a total of 85 states took
the opportunity to sign, ratify or accede to more than 40
multilateral treaties, the majority of which cover human rights,
disarmament, the environment, and international criminal law.
</P>
<P>
The summit finally adopted the "United Nations Millennium
Declaration" in which the world leaders reaffirmed their
commitment to the purposes and principles of the Charter of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The world leaders also pledged to establish a just and lasting
peace all over the world in accordance with the objectives and
principles of the charter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
