<HEADLINE> Three European "Wise Men" Recommend Lifting of Sanctions Against Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Three "wise men" appointed by
the European Union for assessing the political situation in
Austria recommended on Friday a lifting of bilateral sanctions
imposed by 14 other EU countries on Vienna.
</P>
<P>
In a report submitted to French President Jacques Chirac, the
three "wise men" -- former Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
former Spanish Foreign Minister Marcelino Oreja, and German jurist
Jochen Frowein, said that the sanctions will become harmful if the
14 other EU countries don't lift them.
</P>
<P>
They said that the measures have caused nationalist feeling in
Austria whose citizens think that the sanctions are targeted
against them.
</P>
<P>
The three "wise men" were appointed in June by the European
Court of Human Rights for evaluating the Austrian government's
attachment to the common value of human rights and the political
evolution of the far-right Freedom Party led by Joerg Haider,
which joined the government in February .
</P>
<P>
"Our conviction is that the Austrian government respects the
common European values," said the report.
</P>
<P>
EU imposed sanctions against Austria in February, including
the suspension of bilateral cooperation between Vienna and 14
other member countries, minimum contact with Austrian ambassadors,
and refusal to support Austrian candidates in posts of
international organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
