<HEADLINE> George W. Bush Adjusts Campaign Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush adjusted his campaign style
Friday to regain the momentum two months before the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Texas Governor Bush tried his new closer-to-the-people style as
he campaigned near Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, sharing coffee and
answering questions from high-tech factory workers.
</P>
<P>
"This is what I'm good at," he said. "I like meeting people, my
fellow citizens, I like interfacing with them."
</P>
<P>
"We're going to continue to have more conversations with
Americans in settings where they live and work," Bush said.
</P>
<P>
Bush, standing amid workers on the factory floor with a
microphone but no dais or podium, talked about the Social Security
retirement system, his education reform agenda and his 1.3
trillion U.S. dollars tax cut proposal. Afterward, he spent 45
minutes in answering questions from workers.
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor changed his campaign style after top
Republicans are getting increasingly concerned about Democratic
nominee Al Gore's rise in the polls.
</P>
<P>
Polls show Vice-President Gore either even or slightly ahead of
the Texas governor in the presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
Bush Friday campaigned in Pennsylvania and Missouri, two swing
states, and then went back to Texas for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bush's Democratic rival Al Gore promoted his plans
to upgrade education as he campaigned in New Orleans Friday.
</P>
