<HEADLINE> Somalia's New President to Set Up Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's new President
Abbiqassim Salad Hassan said here on Friday that would begin to
set up a government after his return to his country.
</P>
<P>
Hassan, who is here attending the three-day U.N. Millennium
Summit which opened at the U.N. headquarters in New York Wednesday,
said in his meeting with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that he
would start with the naming of a prime minister and the
establishment of government agencies.
</P>
<P>
He said he would need U.N.help.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that while the U.N. is prepared to assist,
there has to be an end of violence that has torn the country apart
over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
The president apologized for the loss of life to U.N.
peacekeepers and aid workers during that period.
</P>
<P>
They reviewed the Djibouti peace process which had culminated
in his election as the president of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Hassan was elected two weeks ago by a parliament operating out
of the neighboring state of Djibouti. His presentation at the
summit ended more than a decade's isolation of his impoverished
nation.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been without a central government since 1991. Clan
leaders from across Somalia gathered in Djibouti in May of this
year to work out a plan to restore some sort of order to the
fractured nation.
</P>
<P>
A 425-member parliament was created three weeks ago with
representatives from all of Somalia's clans and sub-clans.
Elections were promised after a three-year transitional period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
